Title: Lactate Ramp Test
WorkoutDescription: Pre-Test Preparation: Consistency Across Tests: Ensure everything is consistent for effective comparison across tests. Morning of the Test: Nutrition: Have a significant impact on results. Avoid high carbohydrate meals/drinks close to the test to prevent elevated blood glucose and disproportionate energy oxidation from carbohydrates. Recommend fasting for ~3hrs before the test. Warm-Up: Lactate Measurement: Obtain a resting baseline measure of lactate before starting the warm-up. Duration: Around 30-60 minutes, depending on various factors. Can be done prior to official test time in a commercial lab setting. Intensity: Very easy, ideally below 50% of anticipated threshold. The Test: Format: Step test with 5-minute stages, allowing physiological processes to stabilize before increasing to the next level. Continuation: Go to volitional fatigue, regardless of the number of stages completed. Sampling Procedure: Set-Up: Table: Ensure you have a table set at a working height, which is crucial when self-testing on a bike. Hygiene and Organization: Hand Cleaning: Thoroughly clean your hands before starting the test to maintain hygiene. Strip Preparation: Have all the required strips lined up and ready to use, aiming to minimize the time between samplings. Sampling Procedure: Follow this sequence meticulously to ensure accurate and hygienic sampling: Alcohol Swab: Use it to clean the finger that will be lanced. Lancing: Use a sterile lancet to prick the cleaned finger to draw a drop of blood. First Wipe: Use a gauze pad to wipe away the first drop of blood, along with any residual alcohol. Second Wipe (if necessary): If you are particularly sweaty, you may need to wipe away a second drop to ensure a clean sample. Test Strip: Gently place the test strip into the blood drop, ensuring not to touch the skin. The strip is designed to use capillary action to draw up the blood. By following these steps, you can ensure a clean and precise blood sample for your test. Practical Notes: Initial Fitness Estimate: Doesnâ€™t need to be completely accurate; could be from the last test or a recent race. Preparation: Have all materials ready and know the sampling sequence. Erg Mode for Bike Test: Makes it easier for the athlete, allowing focus on the test rather than holding a given power.

Title: 6x20" stomps
WorkoutDescription: Base pace in mostly Z1, with option to ride Z2 once done with sprint work: â€¢10 min Z3 @ 100+ rpm, finishing with a 15" seated sprint at maximal leg speed â€¢6 x 20sec "stomps" - these are done seated, in a big gear (53x15ish), from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration. Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min). In the sprints prioritize speed production via FORM over power production on the meter. Focus on generating power over the top of the pedal stroke (10-2 on the clock).

Title: Ghost of Seiler 0
WorkoutDescription: Warm up for 15-20m progressing from Z1-Z2 - 1x10min high cadence Z3, 100-120 rpm - 5 min recovery - 4x6 min low Z5 (lower end), 2 min Z1 - Low Z2 > Cool Down after intervals.
CoachComments: 1. Goal is highest average across intervals, NOT PR attempt in one interval and the rest low. 2. Start at bottom-miiddle of Z5 in first two intervals, increase if feeling good. - Make sure to eat carbohydrates in meals/snacks before this; if done in early am have a gel before you start and a gel halfway through the ride. - Refuel immediately after with food/shake with 4:1 ratio of carbs to protein; e.g. bowl of oatmeal with almonds

Title: Tastes of Threshold + Torque Accel
WorkoutDescription: Progressive warmup 6x20 sec HARD/40 sec easy shift to a bigger gear each time you hit 90 rpm. First 5 seated, 6th standing. Flush 2x12min alternating 2min 300-320/1min 340-370 8min between 1x8min where you perceive 20-30min race pace to be Start @ 350w as the target and adjust +/- from there Cooldown

Title: Z2
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy warm up to get legs going. Then, goal is aerobic stress. High average power without going over Z3/Tempo (320w) Pick a route where you can stay fairly constant on the pedals, and minimize soft pedaling and coasting. Target a lot of time @ High Z2/Low Z3 (230-280w) 10min easy cool down to flush the effort. - Fueling for Sunday should look like a race day. Good carb rich dinner Saturday night, breakfast of mostly carbs but not such a huge meal that it sits heavy in your gut, dehydrates you, and draws blood from your legs (this relies on having a good dinner Sat night), then race like nutrition on the bike ~70 g of carbs per hour. You're gonna be riding pretty high up the energy burn!

WorkoutDescription: 10 min Z1/Z2 warm up - 1x10min Z3 high cadence (>100) to get loose - 5 min Z1 - 4x7 min low Z5; 2 min recovery; - Low Z2 > Cool Down after intervals.
CoachComments: 1. Goal is highest average across intervals, NOT PR attempt in one interval and the rest low. 2. Start at bottom-middle of Z5 in first two intervals, increase if feeling good. - Make sure to eat carbohydrates in meals/snacks before this; if done in early am have a gel before you start and a gel halfway through the ride. -Refuel immediately after with food/shake with 4:1 ratio of carbs to protein; e.g. bowl of oatmeal with almonds

Title: Blood Pistons 3
WorkoutDescription: Z2 base with efforts spaced through as they fit terrain, in this order: â€¢10 min low Z3 @ 100+ rpm â€¢3 sets of 6 x 60" Z5, < 70 rpm / 2' low Z3, 90+ rpm (12' set) Go Z1 for 5-10 min after each effort before resuming Z2.

Title: 20/40s, Z3
WorkoutDescription: Matti, take from now through the end of November as a period without structure. Exercise and enjoy it for what it gives to your life. But also make a conscious effort to complete the period feeling physically rested. So having high volume or high intensity days is no problem, but the thing to avoid is the fatigue that comes with compounding those days back to back. Overall load should be low, most weeks should be <10 hrs training. Include yoga 2-3x / week. I've put it in TP as a reminder, but do it on whatever days you like.

Title: 6x20" stomps
WorkoutDescription: Base pace in mostly Z1, with option to ride Z2 once done with sprint work: â€¢10 min Z3 @ 100+ rpm, finishing with a 15" seated sprint at maximal leg speed â€¢6 x 20sec "stomps" - these are done seated, in a big gear (53x15ish), from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration. Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min). In the sprints prioritize speed production via FORM over power production on the meter. Focus on generating power over the top of the pedal stroke (10-2 on the clock).

Title: Ski

Title: Gravel / Fartlek Intensity
WorkoutDescription: Get the gravel bike out on the roads and on the dirt a bit. Include some intense efforts, mixed from 1-10' ranging in intensity from tempo to VO2. Do it without much structure, more like picking a hill, or section of road to give it some stick. Make the ride pretty "polarized", meaning throttle back between the intense moments and ride mostly @ HR < 135 bpm. Set it up with the tires / pressure you want to use for race day and gauge how it feels.

Title: VO2 (40/20-Z3-Z4)

Title: 20/40s, Z3
WorkoutDescription: Matti, take from now through the end of November as a period without structure. Exercise and enjoy it for what it gives to your life. But also make a conscious effort to complete the period feeling physically rested. So having high volume or high intensity days is no problem, but the thing to avoid is the fatigue that comes with compounding those days back to back. Overall load should be low, most weeks should be <10 hrs training. Include yoga 2-3x / week. I've put it in TP as a reminder, but do it on whatever days you like.

So having high volume or high intensity days is no problem, but the thing to avoid is the fatigue that comes with compounding those days back to back. Overall load should be low, most weeks should be <10 hrs training. Include yoga 2-3x / week. I've put it in TP as a reminder, but do it on whatever days you like.

Title: 6x20" stomps
WorkoutDescription: Base pace in mostly Z1, with option to ride Z2 once done with sprint work: â€¢10 min Z3 @ 100+ rpm, finishing with a 15" seated sprint at maximal leg speed â€¢6 x 20sec "stomps" - these are done seated, in a big gear (53x15ish), from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration. Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min). In the sprints prioritize speed production via FORM over power production on the meter. Focus on generating power over the top of the pedal stroke (10-2 on the clock).

That doesn't mean it turns into a high intensity affair, it just means it's not about constant pressure on the pedals.
CoachComments: 2-3h easy ride in Z1-Z2 RPE.

Title: Don't Be A Square 1 (ba.ca) - 6x1min; 1x10Z3
WorkoutDescription: Warm up Z1-Z2 10 min - 6x1min Z3 (100-120 rpm cadence), 1 min normal cadence Z1 - 5 min Z1-Z2 - 1x10 min Z3 (100-120 rpm cadence) - 5 min Z1-Z2 - 6x1min Z3 (100-120 rpm cadence), 1 min normal cadence Z1 - Z2 for time. - Pointer - Cadence workouts stress neuromuscular recruitment. The end goal is to feel comfortable producing power at a high cadence. Developing a higher cadence is foundational to optimizing your anaerobic potential in the Build Period.
CoachComments: Matti this is a good workout for today so I left it in. Do Z3 by RPE with a HR ceiling of 160 bpm. Z2 HR ceiling 145 bpm.

Title: Profiling: 30", 4', 12'
WorkoutDescription: Ride easy for 15-20 min to get loose, then do some priming efforts: -5' build from Z3 to Z4 by RPE -3-5 x 15-20" accelerations increasing in effort Spin out, then do the main efforts: -30" max -4' max -12' max Take over 10 min recovery between each effort (this is important!).

Title: Baseline Aerobic Limit Ride (make meat of it 3h)
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy warm up to get legs going. Then, goal is aerobic stress. High average power without going over Z3/Tempo (340w) Pick a route where you can stay pretty constant on pedals then finish up a climb to squeeze it out a bit, and soft pedal home. Target a lot of time @ High Z2/Low Z3 (250-300w) 10min easy cool down to flush the effort. - Fueling should look like a race day. Good carb rich dinner night before, breakfast of mostly carbs but not such a huge meal that it sits heavy in your gut, dehydrates you, and draws blood from your legs then race like nutrition on the bike ~70 g of carbs per hour.
AthleteComments: *12/05/2021 Matti Rowe: 12/15/21: 3h, 269, 146bpm, 4.2%* *12/05/2021 Matti Rowe: Felt good, but numbers kind of sucked. At least I didn't have terrible back pain on this.  I didn't finish shattered. Really want to beat 3/9/19 in '22.*

Title: The Geriatric 1
WorkoutDescription: 1.Couch stretch- Hold for 2 minutes with HUGE emphasis on rolling your pelvis under your torso. This part is key. Leave the foot down on the ground behind you and don't worry about the band. Every day, minimum of 1x/day. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8GEnBM6BGYg 2. Standing pigeon- 2 minutes with focus on belt buckle to belly button and driving the opposite hip toward the table. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=50RTFq9bszA 3. Standing hydrant- Hold 45 seconds + 15 reps after. Both sides. Mandatory to do in front of a mirror. 2 sets if possible. Make sure knee is over foot, pelvis is level, and trunk is neutral. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oY7v_SpDxcc 4.Standing Skate- same as above https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MElyAbCbmGM 5.Single leg squat - Foot behind, 20 reps, mandatory in front of mirror. Make sure knee is over foot, pelvis is level, and trunk is neutral. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bZvKEBn4C2Q

Title: Fixing Anterior Pelvic Tilt
WorkoutDescription: Fixing Anterior Pelvic Tilt Below I have listed five exercises that will help correct an anterior pelvic tilt and help relieve the feeling of tight hamstrings. The focus of the first two exercises is increasing length through the anterior musculature of the hip. The focus of the second two is strengthening the posterior chain and the final exercise to strengthen the anterior core. In general All of these exercises will help, but in you spend most of your day sitting at a desk these exercises in and of themselves will not reverse the damage from hour upon hour of sitting when your hip flexors shortened and your glutes asleep. Minimally, need to do two things, which are annoying: Get a standing desk - you should stand at least â…“ of the day. This will be annoying at first, but itâ€™s essential that you spend some time standing with good posture for parts of the day. Getting a bosu ball for sitting - A bosu ball requires more balance and extra recruitment for your core. Optional - get a â€˜good postureâ€™ halter. I know this seems corney, but it will for you to stop hunching over which promotes better posture. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 1. Front Foot Elevated Split Squat The split squat is a great exercise to open up the anterior hip and also has the added benefit of also improving ankle mobility. Increasing length through your hip flexors will help decrease some of the tension placed on the hamstrings. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3dYFpa-ZT2s&feature=youtu.be 2. Couch Stretch The added benefit of the couch stretch compared to a regular hip flexor stretch is it stretches the rectus femoris, a muscle which is often forgotten. The rectus femoris is a biarticular muscle, meaning it crosses two joints, thus to stretch it, the knee needs to be in flexion while the hips are in extension. The standard, half kneeling hip flexor stretch only targets illiopsoas and not the rectus femoris. When fixing an anterior tilt, it is important to assess both these areas. Squeeze your glute on the same side. This will posteriorly tilt the pelvis and ensure you get a greater stretch in the rectus femoris. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QiKl5UoiG5c 3. Romanian Deadlift The Romanian Deadlift is a great exercise to strengthen the glutes, hamstrings and lower back. Although you will use a lighter load when compared to a regular deadlift, the Romanian Deadlift is arguably greater hamstring stimulus due to it being pure hip extension with minimal movement from the knee. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X1LrH79jxQQ 4. Glute Ham Raise The glute ham raise strengthens the hamstrings at both the hip and the knee joint simultaneously. It works both primary functions, knee flexion and hip extension while also being a closed kinetic chain exercise. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cT6I4K8xiFU&feature=youtu.be 5. Deadbug The deadbug is a great anterior core drill which teaches people to dissociate movement from the lumbar spine and the hips. The goal of this exercise is to maintain neutral spine and not go into over extension as you lower your leg. The cue to focus on is to keep your ribs down and lower back flat against the floor the whole time. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZaCc3AbXLwo&feature=youtu.be 5. Warrior 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_0K-Kuw6DOs

Title: Free Period
WorkoutDescription: Matti, take from now through the end of November as a period without structure. Exercise and enjoy it for what it gives to your life. But also make a conscious effort to complete the period feeling physically rested. So having high volume or high intensity days is no problem, but the thing to avoid is the fatigue that comes with compounding those days back to back. Overall load should be low, most weeks should be <10 hrs training. Include yoga 2-3x / week. I've put it in TP as a reminder, but do it on whatever days you like.

Title: 1 Week No Bike
WorkoutDescription: OK to be active this week - running / hiking, but let's get one full week with no riding and close the door on 2019 and start to open 2020 when back.

Title: Strength (2x12 maintenance squat, dl stays light) + Hip Drive Exercises
WorkoutDescription: We're entering a short high weight phase, you should warm up with a few of the core and isometric hip drive exercises before doing the squats and dead lift work. Squats - do 2 sets x 12 reps @ light to moderate weight. Goal is keeping the movement pattern familiar but starting to give way to increased intensity on the bike. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
CoachComments: Let's work this back in now that we have a bit of space from the race season.
AthleteComments: *11/02/2019 Matti Rowe: Back Squat 3 x 12 20, 12, 12, 12, 12, @ 45, 135, 165, 165, 165, lb B Box Jump 3 x 5 3 x 5 @ 24, 24, 30, in C Deadlift 3 x 12 3 x 12 @ 135, 135, 8, lb D Single Leg Box Jump 3 x 5 3 x 5 @ 24 in E Single Leg Deadlift 2 x 10 2 x 10 @ 18 lb F Stir the Pot 2 x 10 2 x 10 G Plank 3 x 1mi 3 x 1 H Push-Up 3 x MAX 20, 20, 15, 15, I Wide Grip Pull Ups 3 x MAX 5, 4, 3, 3, J Russian Twist 3 x MAX 30, 20, K Bicycle Sit-Ups 3 x 1mi 2 x 1*

Title: Welcome Back to the Bike Ride
WorkoutDescription: No real goals for todays ride other than just to get your body used to pedaling again after a week off the bike. Keep the pace pretty easy zone 1/zone 2 overall. 60-90min total ride time.
CoachComments: Simple general ride; avg HR < 145 bpm
AthleteComments: *11/07/2019 Nate Wilson: OK welcome back. All positive. Looks like HR isn't way out of whack for power or anything. Given the week off the bike was still quite aerobically active that's no surprise. But let's view this now as we're beginning our build to 2020. That doesn't mean no cross training, that doesn't mean it's not fun - but it does mean start doing things with a bigger picture in mind beyond just being active and having fun.*

Title: Zones Reminder (FTP stay @ 360w)
WorkoutDescription: Matti, you've had a pretty active fall and not really lost a ton of fitness. So I'm going to just leave your FTP @ 360w for now. If it's falsely high it's not more than 10-15 watts and I'm pretty sure that even just after 1-2 weeks back on the bike all the Z2/Z3 power will be lining up pretty well with the HR zones we want to target. If it seems way off, I'll take a few watts off the top of the FTP. That said, for the next few weeks focus primarily on RPE and HR to guide your training. Given your peak HR's from 2019 I want to move your LT HR from 175 bpm to 170 bpm - I think this is more realistic for now: LT HR = 170 bpm 1/Recovery < 125 bpm 2/Endurance 125-145 bpm Low 3/Low Tempo 145-153 bpm High 3/High Tempo 153-160 bpm 4/Threshold 160-170 bpm 5/VO2 Max 170-175 bpm 6/Supra Max 175+ bpm

Title: Strength (4x8 heavy squat/plyo PAP + dl) + Hip Drive Exercises
WorkoutDescription: Matti, before starting squats warm up with some foundations, core, and one set of split squat: 3 sets x 10-12 split squat - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtzdcxjEb8s (do first set as warm up and space other 2 sets through workout) Squats - do 4 sets x 6-8 reps @ a weight that is heavy but in control. Start with the weight you were doing for squats last week, and add 10 lbs each set this week to find the point where it is challenging but you're able to complete at least 6 reps well. Follow each squat set with a 30 sec recovery, and then 10x box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 4 sets x 6-8 reps @ moderate-heavy weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
CoachComments: Matti, we want to be increasing weight over the next 3-4 weeks - but doing so gradually. If today feels like perhaps it was too easy, that's good. And you can always increase next session.

Title: Sprint Intro (3x little, 3x big)
WorkoutDescription: Easy pace overall today, with a bit of sprint work: 1x8-10 min Z3 @ 100+ rpm - do on RPE with HR MAX 160 BPM 3x20 sec sprints, done seated, and in the little ring. Only shift once you're really running out of gear. Do these on flat terrain, from "endurance speed". 3x15 sec sprints, done standing, in the big ring, classical sprint. Ideally do these coming off a downhill so you're coming at a bit of speed, again minimize shifts. 3+ min recovery between sprints.
CoachComments: Minimize shifts - think about when you're in a sprint, every time you shift, that is half a second the chain is not driving the cassette forward. If you shift 3x in an 8 second sprint - not so great at speed production - goal is always SPEED.

Title: Z2 HR + HC (5x1)
WorkoutDescription: 1-2h @ HR 125-145 bpm Where it fits: 5x1min, 300-330w, 110+ rpm / 1min recovery
AthleteComments: *11/11/2019 Nate Wilson: Check, check - nice bread and butter ride. It's so easy to dismiss these rides because it doesn't feel like they're the ones that move the needle. But the more I see the more and more I realize really how important these rides. These are the rides that keep guys from falling apart in April, and let you be robust and resilient and just keep pushing.*

Title: SFR Intro (6x3)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, natural at first and then build to some focused time @ 105+ rpm before efforts: 10 min Z3 - HR @ 150-160 bpm, once you get a few min into the effort. 6x3min SFR, 50-60 rpm, 300-330w / 3 min recovery. After SFR, 4x30 sec @ 120+ rpm - not big power, just leg speed.
CoachComments: Matti, I put in 1.5 hours - do anywhere from 1-2 hours based on what you have time for.
AthleteComments: *11/09/2019 Matti Rowe: Second time work fucked me this week.  At least I got the lift in.* *11/11/2019 Nate Wilson: No worries, good work on the lift!*

Title: General End; 3-4h - OK to swap Sat/Sun as you feel
WorkoutDescription: 3-4 hours of simple endurance. Nothing fancy today - mostly Z2. Great to go with a group and be a bit more social on it, depending on if that fits into your day without stress. Each hour do 5 min in the drops @ 100+ rpm; 3-4 x 5 min total.
AthleteComments: *11/10/2019 Matti Rowe: I was kinda garbage today, but ripped a few sprints here and there to keep it fresh along with the drops work. Freaking hot!* *11/11/2019 Nate Wilson: OK, all good. Not a day you needed to feel super amazing, just wanted to get some vol in.*

Title: Hike w/ Trail Running - OK to swap Sat/Sun as you feel
WorkoutDescription: Longer loop - make it more of a hike, possibly something like Green Mtn or Flag. Run on flatter sections and power hike on steeper sections.
CoachComments: Matti, no stress if you don't have time for a hike. This could be a jog from the house, or another simple endurance ride like yesterday.

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling - bonus if time
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: https://stream.foundationtraining.com/programs/12-minute-workout Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Title: NATE - precision hydration sweat test?
WorkoutDescription: https://www.precisionhydration.com/pages/sweat-testing

Title: Z1 Recovery (optional - 30-90 min)
WorkoutDescription: Nice and easy today, keep the cadence light and spend some time with the cadence over 100rpm to flush the legs a bit. 5x30 sec one leg drills
CoachComments: One leg drills = pedaling with one leg unclipped. Focus on smooth pedal stroke, engaging hips and glutes for full contact around the stroke. If challenging shift to a harder gear to keep cadence low, prioritize form over power production.

Title: Sprint Work (4x stomps)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 base pace, with efforts: -10 min Z3, 105+ rpm - MAX HR 160 -2x15sec seated sprints in the little ring, only shifting when you're really running out of gear, keep upper body quiet. -4x20sec "stomps", done seated, in a big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, should only be hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so (adjust gear as necessary). Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min).
CoachComments: Focus on SPRINT EFFICIENCY - meaning the end product is SPEED NOT POWER. So anything that you may do to enhance power that actually inhibits speed, really force yourself to consciously avoid. This includes driving the bike so it's not going as straight as possible, rocking the upper body a lot. Think about driving over the top of the pedal stroke from 10-2 on a clock, and not stomping down excessively at the bottom of the pedal stroke. When the pedals are at 6 o'clock, there's no forward power delivered into the bike.
AthleteComments: *11/13/2019 Matti Rowe: Power meter battery dead.* *11/18/2019 Nate Wilson: Bummer, but glad you got it in! Your legs have no idea whether the meter was working or not!*

Title: TT End + MIXED CAD Z3 (6x3)
WorkoutDescription: 1-2h Z1/Z2 on the TT bike - simple endurance by feel. Where it fits, Z3 cadence work: 6x3min, 300-330w - odd reps (1,3,5) 100+ rpm; even reps (2,4,6) 60-70 rpm. Main efforts: 4 x 8 min 300-330w / 6 min recovery #1 and 3 = 95-120 rpm #2 and 4 = 60-70 rpm Cool Down, spend some time @ 100+ in cool down.

Title: Sprint Work (4x stomps + 4x stand)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 base pace, with efforts: -15 min Z3, 105+ rpm - MAX HR 160 -2x15sec seated sprints in the little ring, only shifting when you're really running out of gear, keep upper body quiet. -4x20sec "stomps", done seated, in a big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, should only be hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so (adjust gear as necessary). -4x20 sec "standing starts", these are just like the stomps, but done out of the saddle - big gear (52x14ish), from near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration up to speed. Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min).
CoachComments: Focus on SPRINT EFFICIENCY - meaning the end product is SPEED NOT POWER. So anything that you may do to enhance power that actually inhibits speed, really force yourself to consciously avoid. This includes driving the bike so it's not going as straight as possible, rocking the upper body a lot. Think about driving over the top of the pedal stroke from 10-2 on a clock, and not stomping down excessively at the bottom of the pedal stroke. When the pedals are at 6 o'clock, there's no forward power delivered into the bike.
AthleteComments: *12/10/2019 Nate Wilson: Glad you got TT work in. Again, it's looking pretty easy by HR. How is it feeling?*

Title: Recovery Themed Day - optional spin, prefer not run unless very easy and < 40 min

WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy warm up to get legs going. Then, goal is aerobic stress. Good carb rich dinner Saturday night, breakfast of mostly carbs but not such a huge meal that it sits heavy in your gut, dehydrates you, and draws blood from your legs (this relies on having a good dinner Sat night), then race like nutrition on the bike ~70 g of carbs per hour. You're gonna be riding pretty high up the energy burn!

Title: Sprint Work (2x stomps + 2x stand + 2x speed sprints)
WorkoutDescription: Ride easy today except efforts: -5 min Z3, 105+ rpm - MAX HR 160 -2x20 sec stomps. -2x20 sec standing starts -2x10 sec SPEED SPRINTS - do these coming off of a bit of a downhill so you have some natural momentum, and then as momentum is just starting to slow pop and take off as hard as you can in the initial pedal strokes and hold onto the speed Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min).
CoachComments: Focus on SPRINT EFFICIENCY - meaning the end product is SPEED NOT POWER. So anything that you may do to enhance power that actually inhibits speed, really force yourself to consciously avoid. This includes driving the bike so it's not going as straight as possible, rocking the upper body a lot. Think about driving over the top of the pedal stroke from 10-2 on a clock, and not stomping down excessively at the bottom of the pedal stroke. When the pedals are at 6 o'clock, there's no forward power delivered into the bike.

Title: Z2 w/ Surges < Tempo Finish (30')
WorkoutDescription: Ride at a steady endurance clip. Keep good zone 2 pressure (210-250w) on the pedals all day. Every 20 min do a 20 sec seated acceleration, alternating one rep high torque / one rep high cad. High Torque = shift to bigger gear each time you hit 85 rpm High Cad = 110+ rpm all the way In last 60 min - finish with a 30 min Z3 climb (300-340w), can push into Z4 in final 5 min by feel. Make sure you stay on top of fueling throughout the ride so you can perform at the end.

Title: Baseline Aerobic Limit Ride (make meat of it 3.5-4h)
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy warm up to get legs going. Then, goal is aerobic stress. High average power without going over Z3/Tempo (340w) Pick a route where you can stay pretty constant on pedals then finish up a climb to squeeze it out a bit, and soft pedal home. Target a lot of time @ High Z2/Low Z3 (250-300w) 10min easy cool down to flush the effort. - Fueling should look like a race day. Good carb rich dinner night before, breakfast of mostly carbs but not such a huge meal that it sits heavy in your gut, dehydrates you, and draws blood from your legs then race like nutrition on the bike ~70 g of carbs per hour.
AthleteComments: *01/20/2020 Matti Rowe: I couldnâ€™t get outside- life exploded and it was Zwift or too short.* *01/21/2020 Nate Wilson: Well, can't argue with the data in terms of showing improved aerobic capacity. Most power you've ever done for one of these - 306w for 3h35m, and 1.9% drift - which is very hard to manage on the trainer in my opinion. Let's hope we can translate this from Zwift wattage to bike RACING. But looks great Matti. Nice work.*

Title: Strength (2x12 - light weight)
WorkoutDescription: Matti, warm up with foundations moves - goal of today is maintenance of movement patterns and minimal fatigue from the session. Squats - do 2 sets x 12 reps @ light to moderate weight. Goal is keeping the movement pattern familiar but starting to give way to increased intensity on the bike. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).

Title: VO2 / LT Mix (5x5')
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up + a few min Z3 opener. Then efforts: 5 x 40 sec @ 400-450w / 20 sec easy (controlled) 5 min @ 350-380w 5 x 40 sec @ 400-450w / 20 sec easy 5 min @ 350-380w 5 x 40 sec @ 400-450w / 20 sec easy 4 min recovery between each 5 min block.
AthleteComments: *01/26/2020 Nate Wilson: Glad to have you outside! How'd the power feel sitting steady on LT?* *01/26/2020 Matti Rowe: It actually felt really really good.*

Title: TT: Strength/LT/Strength Sandwich (2x12') + 4x90 supra LT
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 1-2 x 3 min ramp from Z3 to Z4 (do on feel, and do a second one if you feel you need it, otherwise one is good) 2x12 min "sandwiches" as follows... 4 min 300-330w, 60-70 rpm 4 min 340-370w, self selected cad 4 min 300-330w, 60-70 rpm 8 min recovery between the 2x12', 4' recovery after the 2nd rep, then... 4x90 sec @ 370-420w / 60 sec recovery Cool down
AthleteComments: *01/26/2020 Nate Wilson: Looks like a tough one - legs look sapped by the time they got to the 90s. These workouts will pay off!* *01/26/2020 Matti Rowe: Yeah it was so early and I was mentally stretching by the time I got to the 90s*

Title: General w/ Progressives
WorkoutDescription: Easy start, then ride mostly Z2 with efforts spaced through: 2 x 5 min builds from 280w to 360w 1 x 2 min where you perceive 5 min max to be 1 x 10-15 sec sprint Full recovery between efforts.
CoachComments: Carb rich dinner tonight!

Title: SFR Over/Under (3x8')
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 base with efforts: -10' low Z3 (270-300w), done on flats @ 100+ rpm aim for "aero efficiency" -3x8' on climb alt 3' SFR (50-60 rpm, 320-350w) / 1min high Z4 (370-400w, 90+ rpm) Full recovery between. On way home, do 6min block with Z2 baseline 8 sec sprint every min.

Title: TT: 6/4/90 (2x)
WorkoutDescription: Run through TT warm up (22' total): 10 min gradual ramp from easy to ~260w, in the second part use mostly 95+ rpm 2 min easy 3 min ramp on RPE from high Z3 to high Z4 2 min easy 90 sec ramp from mid Z4 to VO2 2 min easy 2x through: 6 min @ 320-350w (3 min easy) 4 min @ 350-380w (3 min easy) 90 sec @ 380-410w (3 min easy, then next set) Cool down
AthleteComments: *02/01/2020 Matti Rowe: Bad planning today.  Didn't get it done.*

Title: General End
WorkoutDescription: 3h general endurance by feel or with a group - enjoy! Skiing is OK / GREAT today, or if you prefer to do a Zwift ride ok to go shorter and higher intensity.
AthleteComments: *02/02/2020 Matti Rowe: Dude, don't hit me with a mean comment.  I tried to go ride twice.  I got smacked with insane mechanical karma today and both my rear derailleur cables snapped on both my Orbea and Tarmac - I could not shift out of the big ring on either.  No joke. Unreal timing.  It was freaking beautiful out and I couldn't wait to go hit it.  Go figure. So it was skiing or... Nothing. So I skied. I have spare cables and housing so I'll try to get one bike up and running tomorrow and get in a decent ride, but everything has to go perfectly.* *02/02/2020 Nate Wilson: That sucks! But skiing for 3 hours is hardly a bad alternative - not like you just sat on the couch and thought about riding.*

Title: Bookend Ride (2 sets of 2x6' pyramid efforts)
WorkoutDescription: Bookend ride = 2 sets of identical efforts, first set in the first 1.5 hours, second set in final 90 min. Build fatigue resistance and fueling ability. Set 1 = 2 x 6 min of 1 min @ 420-450w, 1 min @ 380-410w, 2 min @ 320-350w, 1 min @ 380-410w, 1 min @ 420-450w (8 min Z2 between - do these continuous up a climb so it's 20 min total block) Middle = Z1-3, hilly terrain - accumulate some tempo on feel, but not with a structured plan Set 2 = 2 x 6 min of 1 min @ 420-450w, 1 min @ 380-410w, 2 min @ 320-350w, 1 min @ 380-410w, 1 min @ 420-450w (8 min Z2 between - do these continuous up a climb so it's 20 min total block)
CoachComments: 70-80g of carbs per hour!!

Title: Broken VO2 (3 x 6x40/20)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 10 min Z3 on feel 3 sets of 6x40 sec @ 440-490w / 20 sec recover - control on first two sets and then push on third set if you're good. 5 min rec between sets. Cool down
AthleteComments: *02/10/2020 Matti Rowe: 3rd set started to bite, but I didn't collapse.* *02/11/2020 Nate Wilson: OK great. These are the workouts that can really make a difference in Redlands. Redlands is not an avg power race, it's totally a volume of intensity race and a raw intensity race.*

WorkoutDescription: Warmup, then efforts (3x10'): 3x20 sec seated acceleration, 40 sec easy 7 min Z3 (300-330w) 5 min Z4 (360-390w) Rec between 3x10' = 5-6 min. Cool down
AthleteComments: *02/10/2020 Matti Rowe: Felt pretty damn good honestly.  I'm finding that my 20 second power really blows, but on the flip side I seem to be able to hold power at a lower band, call it 500ish, for twice as long and repeat it.* *02/11/2020 Nate Wilson: Yeah and I also really believe that power 30" and below suffers a lot on the trainer compared to what you can do outside. So perhaps we'll see some change there as well with more outdoor time.*

Title: Body Work 2 (mixed hips/glutes/core) - read through, added some moves
WorkoutDescription: Warm up / activation with Founders pose - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vOgxWp0WyiI 7 way hips (10-15 reps each way): https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iLTBIaHU5iw 10-15x push up 15 reps body weight squats (slow, and only as deep as you can control the motion) Bird dog plank (10 reps each side, no foam roller under knees) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wiFNA3sqjCA 15-20x glute bridge (focus on digging heels into ground and pulling towards glutes, to engage hamstrings) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=usDCGz_Vv2k Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo 10 reps single leg hamstring bridge (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Single leg squat (5-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE
CoachComments: Added some moves this week - single leg hamstring bridge, side plank with leg lift and single leg squat

Title: Tempo Stack + PoP
WorkoutDescription: Do 3x 20-30 min front range climbs @ 300-330w In the final hour do some anaerobic efforts as follows: 20 sec hard (40 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 40 sec hard (20 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 20 sec hard Just on feel for now.
AthleteComments: *02/10/2020 Matti Rowe: Bullet proof leg day. Hit me pretty hard an hour after the fact and I fell asleep on a chair - that's a first. I also had an emergency sodium Skratch bomb after because I figured I shipped insane amounts of sodium in the basement.* *02/11/2020 Nate Wilson: Dang man. These days are good - I just truly do want to be careful with them. As we get into the period now ~6 weeks out from JMSR I want to make sure you're coming into the mindset of making sure you have the energy for the intensity days and not wringing the towel dry in training. I guess my thought on that would be like  a day like today in the weeks to come, you might get more out of it come JMSR to have the volume be a bit lower and just take confidence from feeling bullet proof and not taking it to exhaustion BECAUSE you feel bullet proof. But I also realize this specific weekend we had outlined as a volume block, so I don't mean to come across as admonishing this rather I just want to think about the weeks ahead.*

Title: TT Marker
WorkoutDescription: 10-15 min easy spinning, start to mentally focus on the task ahead and center yourself - relaxed and ready to dig. 3-5 min in low tempo, reaching into high tempo 3min progression from low Z4 to high Z4 90 sec progression from high Z4 to mid Z5 Each of the above 3 is it's own step - do 2-3 min of easy spinning between each step. Then - do this course at TT race pace - https://www.strava.com/routes/16050083 Think about breaking down the course to ride fastest across it, beyond just the avg power.
CoachComments: This is going to hurt for now - but it gives us a really important feedback point of how you're feeling creating race pace power in the new TT position - as well as a nice data point to build from. Let's see how you've responded to the strength work so far.
AthleteComments: *02/23/2020 Matti Rowe: Just rode. Had shit sleep + sick kids = clear my head.* *02/24/2020 Nate Wilson: Copy that. We'll get a good push at Frostbite.*

Title: 3x8 TT Speed
WorkoutDescription: 10-15 min easy spin, then run through TT warm up: 10 min ramp from easy to ~260w 2 min easy 3 min ramp from mid Z3 to mid Z4 RPE 2 mine asy 90 sec ramp from mid Z4 to mid Z5 RPE Flush legs 4-5 min then begin efforts: 3x8m @ RPE 8-9 / 10 min recovery First two reps, lock in on "hard, controlled", final rep try to push your power beyond the first two reps. Long recovery to focus on quality efforts.

Title: Aerobic Cap + Tired Torque Sprints
WorkoutDescription: Steady aerobic capacity day... Base @ 220-250w 3x 20-25min climbs @ 320-350w + 15min recovery after before resume base Final hour, do some torque sprints... 6x20 sec hard accelerations / 40 sec recovery - alternating one rep high torque, one rep high cad. High Torque = shift to a bigger gear each time you hit 85 rpm High Cad = 110+ rpm, leg speed all the way
AthleteComments: *03/01/2020 Matti Rowe: I suck. Oh well.* *03/03/2020 Nate Wilson: Even if it was a bit rough around the edges, the 5h vol day is really positive. I also think we see these bad days most commonly when you string together the blocks of 5-6 days consecutive load without a recovery day. We have to remember the value in true recovery and that a day that is "just endurance power" or a day that is skiing doesn't mean it's recovery just because you weren't doing specific hard work on the bike. It's perhaps mental recovery, but the body is still human.* *03/03/2020 Klokka Skaddla: Truth. And I need to hydrate better. I had only two for 3 hours and it was way hotter than I thought*

Title: TT: 6/4/90 (1x)
WorkoutDescription: Run through TT warm up (22' total): 10 min gradual ramp from easy to ~260w, in the second part use mostly 95+ rpm 2 min easy 3 min ramp on RPE from high Z3 to high Z4 2 min easy 90 sec ramp from mid Z4 to VO2 2 min easy 1x through: 6 min @ 320-350w (3 min easy) 4 min @ 350-380w (3 min easy) 90 sec @ 380-410w (3 min easy, then next set) Cool down

Title: TT
WorkoutDescription: WARM UP ------------ 10 min gradual ramp from easy to ~260w, in the second part use mostly 95+ rpm 2 min easy 3 min ramp on RPE from high Z3 to high Z4 2 min easy 90 sec ramp from mid Z4 to VO2 2 min easy RACE ------- Let's discuss pacing once we see the weather. Long / leisurely cool down to achieve 2-2.5h total vol on the day (depending on timing / logistics).

Title: VO2: 4x4
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 12min build increasing power every 4min (280 < 320 < 360) 4x4min VO2 / 4min recovery - goal is maximal power you can do across the set without dropping as you go. So first couple should be hard but in control. Cool down

AthleteComments: *04/02/2020 Matti Rowe: Legs dinked from yesterday.* *04/06/2020 Nate Wilson: Yeah it's a two days preceding that sneaks up on you. None of that stuff was crazy flash, but you did pretty much near 2h worth of Z3 to Z4 work in Tues/Wed, and that just takes the edge off being able to do best capable VO2 efforts. And when you do the VO2 with too much load in the legs, it just takes the edge off the power so it turns into more of a training high RPE but not really ability to push big power. But overall this was still pretty quality, with the last one still being 425w.*

Title: Z2 + Sprint Blocks (10/20 - 3x3')
WorkoutDescription: Z2 base + some sprint efforts: 3 x 3' blocks of 10" acceleration / 20" recovery Go recovery for 5' after each 3' effort then resume Z2.
AthleteComments: *04/09/2020 Matti Rowe: Fresh material?  I was a little confused on what the 'acceleration' was - an all out sprint?  Seated? Standing? - I did the first set seated and the other two standing.* *04/13/2020 Matti Rowe: Bump* *04/13/2020 Nate Wilson: Ah hey, thanks! Yeah so the idea is to have it be a bit closer to simulating the final 1500m of a field sprint or even sprinting out of a break where you have to cover a few accelerations in short time frame before the final big one. So visualize that in the feeling - that they shouldn't be max sprints, basically just jumps until the final one and then go full. Mix them seated and standing just how you probably would in a race. I think it's good to do some of them standing so you deal with a bit more of the stress that comes when you're standing. Because in a race realistically some of them would be hard enough that you'd have no choice but to go standing.*

Title: TT Ladder @ 330-340w
WorkoutDescription: Warm up with Z1-Z2 pedaling and a few min of tempo before starting the main set. Main Set = accumulate time @ 330-340w done in chunks. Start with 3' @ 330-340w, and add 2' to each consecutive chunk until you get to one long enough that you can't hold 330-340w. Once you hit the "limit duration", step back down the ladder in descending time chunks until you can't hold onto 330-340w. Once you can't hold onto 330-340w the workout is over. Recover for 2 min between each chunk - so the recovery is pretty limited. Example... 3' @ 330-340w 5' @ 330-340w 7' @ 330-340w 9' @ 330-340w - if you can't hold the power here, then you start going back down, 2' @ a time. Cool down
AthleteComments: *04/23/2020 Matti Rowe: ðŸ”¨ðŸ”¨ðŸ”¨!!* *04/27/2020 Nate Wilson: 3' @ 358w 5' @ 346w 7' @ 344w 9' @ 335w 7' @ 340w 5' @ 336w 3' @ 344w So got 42' in the bin, and elapsed it's 51' @ 317NP. What do you think of using the box N of Hygiene, or something similar? Idea being to take out the factor of increasing elevation as this workout keeps getting better and also to not fool the power we can do with aid on a climb. Overall Lefthand is pretty shallow so it works pretty well. But I think we can lure ourselves into some false confidences compared to the flat. So made it to 9', let's see if you can get farther next time! Does it make sense the way the workout is written? Title: Strength (2x12 - light weight)
WorkoutDescription: Matti, warm up with foundations moves - goal of today is maintenance of movement patterns and minimal fatigue from the session. Squats - do 2 sets x 12 reps @ light to moderate weight. Goal is keeping the movement pattern familiar but starting to give way to increased intensity on the bike. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).

Title: TT Ladder @ 330-340w
WorkoutDescription: Warm up with Z1-Z2 pedaling and a few min of tempo before starting the main set. Main Set = accumulate time @ 330-340w done in chunks. Start with 3' @ 330-340w, and add 2' to each consecutive chunk until you get to one long enough that you can't hold 330-340w. Once you hit the "limit duration", step back down the ladder in descending time chunks until you can't hold onto 330-340w. Once you can't hold onto 330-340w the workout is over. Recover for 2 min between each chunk - so the recovery is pretty limited. Example... 3' @ 330-340w 5' @ 330-340w 7' @ 330-340w 9' @ 330-340w - if you can't hold the power here, then you start going back down, 2' @ a time. Cool down
AthleteComments: *05/05/2020 Matti Rowe: I think I'm being a bit of a bitch and not going as hard as I can. I should probably be in the mid 160s with this and I'm letting myself get too comfortable. Strength/mobility work is moving the needle and I'm feeling way more comfortable staying turtled and laying out the gear.* *05/11/2020 Nate Wilson: Progress bit by bit. I like the idea of staying with this workout because we can really tangibly track progress. What do you think?* *05/11/2020 Nate Wilson: It definitely shouldn't be easy. For reference last week on Flag in a sub-max effort you avg'd 165 and the last 7' were 173 (HR). So the effort should be at least that high in these efforts. The first few steps are short enough HR may not always get that high - but unless you feel quite fatigued, than yeah if HR is just in 150s, I agree - you need to push into these more.*

Title: TT Marker
WorkoutDescription: 10-15 min easy spinning, start to mentally focus on the task ahead and center yourself - relaxed and ready to dig. 3-5 min in low tempo, reaching into high tempo 3min progression from low Z4 to high Z4 90 sec progression from high Z4 to mid Z5 Each of the above 3 is it's own step - do 2-3 min of easy spinning between each step. Then - do this course at TT race pace - https://www.strava.com/routes/16050083 Think about breaking down the course to ride fastest across it, beyond just the avg power.
AthleteComments: *05/18/2020 Nate Wilson: Dang man that one is solid, and makes the power you were doing in workouts the past couple of weeks look kind of like a joke. I'm completely ignoring the HR as it's clearly a bit off, just from looking at the graph. But if you did 15' @ 350w on those kind of ladder workouts we should be pushing the pieces above this pace, because the idea is it's a workout that "lifts up" your TT pace by doing shorter chunks above what you can currently do. So aim for more like 360w. Also on the upcoming progressive efforts we should aim to finish the last leg above this pace, so 360-370w. I'll update the upcoming workouts with some of these details. I'm glad we got this effort in because it shows you what you can do. So carry some swagger into these next workouts.*

Title: Long Rhythm Change (2x30')
WorkoutDescription: An endurance ride with the goal of incorporating 2x long blocks of rhythm change. Each block is 30' (if going well) done as follows: 5' "pre-load" - 300-330w, 95+ rpm 20' holding 320-350w base, do a 10" surge @ 450-550w every 2' Last 5' lift pace to 370-400w, end effort early if can't stay 370+ These will be pretty tough! Title: 5 Lap Flag
WorkoutDescription: Take 5 laps @ 275-280w. Lock in on that pace as a familiarizer with the potential Everesting pace, even though you may be able to do more for 5 laps. If you want to squeeze it down and do more in the 5th lap you can. Use today to test out protocol of a few items: -Take 35-40g of carbs / lap - bar or rice cake @ top + bottle to drink during the lap up -Have bottles in cooler @ top and ride each lap with 1 bottle that you get through by top -32t cassette -Clean descents
AthleteComments: *06/27/2020 Matti Rowe: I learned a lot: 1. Need more stack under stem.  Back was tweaking on 5/6th reps. 2. No way in hell I'm riding to the base. 3. I need to start really early (like 4 am) for two reasons: The first is to avoid more of the heat.  The second is avoiding more traffic (it's pretty bad). 4. I rolled on a 30t today, I'm going to want that 32t for sure. 5. I brought 5 water bottles with me and by 5th lap I was out - I just can't get so far behind on hydration - I'll just fall apart. 6. Descent time without traffic is comfortably sub 10.  With traffic and a small stop to refresh a bottle it's more like 13minutes. 7. I think sub 35 laps are doable, but it's going to depend entirely on fueling.* *06/29/2020 Nate Wilson: Looks like the numbers line up pretty well - since you were mostly doing 285-290w and 33' laps. So I think you can take 275w and not be over 35'. I still think that is the # to start at and you pick it up as you go on if you feel good. Really good notes though. Especially to put more stack under the stem. The only thing I'm wondering is if with a 32t your back wouldn't bother you as much? But I think in general adding some stack would be AOK. Yeah for sure I think you need to drink a bottle / lap. I would just make the routine that you grab a bottle out of the cooler @ the top of the climb and you have to drink it by the top. I think if you stick on that schedule you'll pee a lot but you'll be pretty hydrated. If the bottle is 25-35g of carbs you don't need to eat anything that lap, if it isn't that rich you need to eat something that is ~30g of carbs. Basically you want to take 30-40g of carbs / lap. And yeah - to ride there on the day of seems like asking for trouble! It should be plenty big on it's own.*

Title: 3x8 TT Speed
WorkoutDescription: Z1-Z2 to get out of town, then run through TT warm up: 10 min progressive build from easy to low Z3 2 min easy 3 min build Z3-Z4 2 min easy 90 sec build Z4-Z5 (skip this if don't need it). Spin out legs, then main efforts: 3x8' @ RPE 8-9 - done on same stretch of road, recovery time is time it takes to ride back to start. Gauge on RPE more than a given #, and ride the "course", undulating power to maximize speed. First two reps, lock in on "hard, controlled", final rep try to get to a farther point down the road than the first 2 reps. Go as easy as you like home, don't think about power.
AthleteComments: *07/13/2020 Matti Rowe: I felt good in the position, powerful and fast.  Lifting and steady mobility work makes a huge difference.* *07/13/2020 Nate Wilson: Nice one Matti! Now we're riding the TT bike. Took some grinding, but this workout is a real corner turner.*

Pros - Super wide handlebar, more stack under stem, less chance for a back pain, disc breaks better for descending overall. Cons - 2 pounds heavier than Tarmac. Title: Free Climbs
WorkoutDescription: 2-2.5h with climbs taken by feel @ free pace.
AthleteComments: *08/13/2020 Matti Rowe: I wanted to do two Flagstaff efforts today with varied rhythm but I was empty. That's the second bad intensity workout I've had this week. I think I'm a little buried from loads of diesel work. My observation is that it is easy to get carried away with diesel work because you can be boxed and still ride forever or do loads of tempo without noticing that holding Z7 for 90 seconds or pushing into threshold puts you on the floor. I'm going to get really into napping.* *08/16/2020 Nate Wilson: Definitely and this is a lot of my issue with chasing CTL or doing too much sustained load. Sure you can keep racking up days with time @ 300w but ultimately there's a lot more fatigue in the background than it seems like until we try some top end. It'll be good to actually step away from the diesel stuff for a bit and get into some snappier stuff. But with that also make the recovery days recovery - and don't get sucked into just turning every easy day into 90' @ 250w or such. Proper day of HVILE Monday.* *08/16/2020 Nate Wilson: Running is also pretty new for you and really dulls the legs so I wouldn't also discredit the running - especially 13.5k the day before! - for some of that sensation.*

Title: Classic Sprint Work
WorkoutDescription: Ride very easy today and focus on sprints: â€¢3 x 20sec "stomps" - these are done seated, in a big gear (53x15ish), from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration. â€¢3x20 sec "standing starts" - these are just like the stomps, but done out of the saddle - big gear (52x14ish), from near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration up to speed. Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min). In the sprints prioritize speed production via FORM over power production on the meter. Focus on generating power over the top of the pedal stroke (10-2 on the clock).

Title: Running
AthleteComments: *08/18/2020 Nate Wilson: Again, also keeping in mind that the running really dulls the legs. I think the running is great, but it's really easy to add in running and then you end up never taking any easier or recovery days. With the amount of running you've done - there's no way 15k is a day we can't expect to take out of you a bit.* *08/18/2020 Matti Rowe: Agreed. For some reason my joints have adapted to this quickly so I'm getting a little sparky on these runs.*

AthleteComments: *08/24/2020 Matti Rowe: Howdyshell came down and we threw down.  Tried to run the sin away.* *08/28/2020 Nate Wilson: 3x pretty long runs this week. Let's be really paying attention to how you're body is feeling. From the file it's looking ok but you'll just have to be really honest with yourself on how you feel. As long as we're staying away from running back to back days for now this is probably ok. The fundamental issue with running is that the muscle adapts to change quicker than the bone, and thus is the reason you can feel good and wind up with a stress fracture. So just something to err on the side of caution with.*

Title: High Z2
WorkoutDescription: Let's keep the vol pulled back today so that you don't create too much deficit with a big kJ ride but stimulate the top of the aerobic system. Once warmed up, ride the majority of the day @ 250-300w. Use the whole zone so you go on the lower end on flat / downhill and higher end on climbs / rollers. 3-3.5h total ride time.

Title: Loaded Efforts (90" Buffer)
WorkoutDescription: Main efforts today, done as follows: 3-5min Z3 @ 100+ rpm (300-330w) to start 1.5 min attack on feel + 30" recovery after Steady progression Z3-Z4 to top (320 -> 375w) You can augment the set duration a bit based on terrain / which climbs you use. Aim for 3-4 sets of 8-15 min total (4 sets if mostly closer to 8' and 3 sets if 15').
AthleteComments: *09/14/2020 Nate Wilson: Already mentioned on email but would prefer to see less focus on the Z3-Z4 progression and more on the 1.5' buffer - that's the part to prioritize. However just see now you had a big run in your legs! That top end power just becomes a ton less accessible on legs tired from running. So perhaps just all you had today - the body can only do what it can do!*

Title: Rhythm Change Sets
WorkoutDescription: 3x 12-18 min sets with change of pace. These can be done as specific time intervals or just on climbs bottom to top. Do in this order: Set 1 = Z3 base + 15" attack every 2' Set 2 = Alternating 2.5 min Z3 / 30" VO2+ Set 3 = Alternating 3 min Z3 / 1 min VO2 Ride base in Z2 with Z1 for 5-10 min after each set, or on descents.

Title: Road Cycling
AthleteComments: *09/21/2020 Matti Rowe: I only had two hours today so I did the 90 Buffers - best workout of the week.  I'm OK with missing a big long one this week since I have plenty of endurance in the legs but have drifted away from top end quite a bit so I actually left this feeling really good about it.  I have Monday and Tuesday off from work and will probably do one long ride and one shorter, depending.  My relatives are coming back this weekend so a long ride might not be in the cards for me.  I know it wasn't the best week, but I'm happy I finally got some intensity in and avoided lots of zeros.* *09/21/2020 Nate Wilson: Yeah I agree, you have plenty of endurance work. And glad to see you get some top end work in. I'm not too stressed if you don't get a long ride in. You racked up such a massive "base" this summer that the endurance won't just shrivel up. I'd say make this next weekend quite loose since you have family in town. One day off and one day where you just sneak out and hammer when you have some space is good. I'll put a workout in, but don't worry about being too dedicated to it if you end up doing something else.*

Title: VO2: 4x4
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 12min build increasing power every 4min (280 < 320 < 360) 4x4min VO2 / 4min recovery - goal is maximal power you can do across the set without dropping as you go. So first couple should be hard but in control. Cool down

Title: Running
AthleteComments: *10/13/2020 Nate Wilson: Now that you've gotten a decent bit of running in I'll give you a little challenge. Try and increase your step frequency - your cadence. Your averaging around 160-170 steps a min, see if you can shorten up some of those steps and make more of them. More steps usually means hitting the ground for less time and not as hard - think about using that as a vehicle for trying to stay as "low" to the ground as possible. You want to be running forward, not jumping up and down with some forward movement.* *10/13/2020 Matti Rowe: Huh - right on!  I'd never thought about that before. I'll give it a shot!*

Title: Strength
WorkoutDescription: Matti, warm up with foundations moves - goal of today is maintenance of movement patterns and minimal fatigue from the session. Squats - do 2 sets x 12 reps @ light to moderate weight. Goal is keeping the movement pattern familiar but starting to give way to increased intensity on the bike. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
AthleteComments: *10/08/2020 Matti Rowe: Sore as today*

Title: Hill Sprints (8x)
WorkoutDescription: 10-20 min easy jogging warm up Then on a moderately steep hill (5-8%) do some sprints... 8x12 sec maximum sprints, focus on picking up knees and a quick turnover rather than long bounding steps. Recover for 1.5-2 min between each sprint. Rest of the time easy jogging to complete 30-60 min of total running.
CoachComments: Matti I think these are great actually for prep for the bike as well - neuromuscular power and hip drive.
AthleteComments: *10/10/2020 Matti Rowe: F me sprints are hard.  I did a few less to err on the side of caution.  I felt a little strain in the last one but I don't think I pulled anything.* *10/13/2020 Nate Wilson: If you're going to turn the sprints day into a longer day I'd encourage you to do the sprints earlier in the day. Do them after 15-20 min of running MAX so that you're fresh and hit them with focus and good form. You should also do the recovery very easy between, as in the 2 min recovery between should be 30-45" of walking then moving into a light jog before the next one. This is all about quality mechanics and not about making it an aerobic load type workout.*

Title: Fartlek: 6k of 1:1
WorkoutDescription: Warm up with 15-20 min of easy jog, then begin the main efforts: 6km "fartlek" of 1 min fast / 1 min easy jog (repeat for 6k) For the "fast" the goal is that you're running above normal endurance pace but it actually feels quite comfortable for the duration. You should finish each 1 min block feeling like you could've run another min at that pace, and be able to comfortably transition to a jog rather than needing to stop and walk. If you do need to walk as the set goes on that is ok, but start out trying to maintain a light jog of around 5:30-6:00 min / km for the 1' easy blocks. Easy jog cool down.
CoachComments: Totally ok to just make this a crosstrain day or a light jog, but I put in this session if it's something fun.

Title: Gravel Endurance (optional AnCap)
WorkoutDescription: 1-2h open endurance on the gravel grinder. If you want to add a bit of spice in, try this... 1 set of 8 x 30" MAX / 120" recovery
AthleteComments: *10/26/2020 Nate Wilson: I really believe throwing in the anaerobic work is good so your legs don't forget about high power. BUT I really encourage you that if you're going to do it, rather than do stuff like 40/20s where it becomes a more aerobic exercise with HR staying more elevated because of short recovery - do stuff with longer recovery and focus on maximal power production. So this should be at least a 1:2 work:recovery ratio - so 30" / 60" as a compromise if doing 120" recovery is mind numbing.*

Title: Hill Sprints (8x) + Tempo (2k)
WorkoutDescription: 10-20 min easy jogging warm up Then on a moderately steep hill (5-8%) do some sprints... 8x12 sec maximum sprints, focus on picking up knees and a quick turnover rather than long bounding steps. Recover for 1.5-2 min between each sprint. After the hill sprints jog easy for 3-5 min and then do... 2 km @ a stiff but controlled pace you feel you could sustained for ~35-40' @ maximum. Rest of the time easy jogging to complete 30-60 min of total running.
CoachComments: Matti I think these are great actually for prep for the bike as well - neuromuscular power and hip drive.
AthleteComments: *10/26/2020 Nate Wilson: Sweet, that looks more like what we're after with the hill sprints! And nice work on the tempo. That stride frequency (cadence) was in a great place on the 2k segment - 180 steps / min, which is like 90 rpm on the bike.*

Title: TT Bike - Free
WorkoutDescription: 1-2h on TT bike. No specific training work, but get on the bike and remind yourself of the position. Use this day to actively think about the position while you're riding and make some notes afterwards to take to the testing with you. One of the big things I've learned is that often the position you can hold the best is what ends up being the most aero in an actual race, because as soon as you are moving and fidgeting drag goes way up. So think about anything in your position right now that doesn't feel sustainable - stuff like if you're using the arms to holds yourself up a lot so you can't stay committed to the sticks, can't keep head down, etc.

Title: TT (3x12) + HC
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, gear limited to the little ring, 105+ rpm where terrain allows. Then efforts: 3x12min 300-330w, 60-70 rpm / 5min recovery between. Do as reps on lefthand. Coming back in 36, do... 3x1min @ 320-350w, 110+ rpm / 1min recovery (prioritize cadence over power).
AthleteComments: *11/02/2018 Matti Rowe: Smh. I gotta hit up Zach again - my body has adapted to the road bike fit and now the TT fit feels fugged. Some adjustments helped, but it's just wrong. On the bright side, I got in 2 intervals in a TT position, which is way better than not having any time in a TT position.* *11/05/2018 Nate Wilson: Not to say that taking another look at the TT fit is a bad thing to do BUT I would also keep in mind that TT fit may feel bad just because you may have tightened up a bit in response to the new road fit. In my mind that doesn't necessarily mean change the TT fit to react - just give it a couple workouts and observe. I'd like to see if you feel any different this week on the TT workout. Sometimes you may just have days where you're not quite sitting on the TT bike right, but it doesn't necessarily mean changing the fit is the answer.* *11/05/2018 Matti Rowe: Copy that!*

Title: Winter Zones (FTP 360 --> 350)
WorkoutDescription: Matti, I'm just taking a touch off the FTP / zones as we move into winter. This is probably more reflective of where raw power will be post break. As you build back up we'll push up with time. For now you can keep these power zones in mind: FTP 350w ----------- 1/Recovery < 190w 2/Endurance 190-260 Low 3/Low Tempo 260-300 High 3/High Tempo 300-330 4/Threshold 330-370 5/VO2 Max 370-450 6/Supra Max 450+

Title: Transition Strength Workout
WorkoutDescription: Read through the attached document and follow the instructions. The main goals here are to prevent injury by stretching the muscles that get shortened with cycling and also strengthening the overall body. Don't hesitate to ask if you've got any questions.
CoachComments: Let's keep doing some work over the next couple of months - but back off and make it a bit lighter. Let me know what you think, and if we want to mix in some more work we can. I'd like to see us in the big picture be back to lifting harder around December, and doing the meaty part of the workout as squats or hex bar deads followed by plyo - this is a great way to improve fast twitch recruitment, and get more out of your plyos.

Title: TT Marker - let's get a gauge on where you're at on the TT bike, that we can revisit
WorkoutDescription: 10-15 min easy spinning, start to mentally focus on the task ahead and center yourself - relaxed and ready to dig. 3-5 min in low tempo, reaching into high tempo 3min progression from low Z4 to high Z4 90 sec progression from high Z4 to mid Z5 Each of the above 3 is it's own step - do 2-3 min of easy spinning between each step. Then - do this course at TT race pace - https://www.strava.com/routes/16050083 Think about breaking down the course to ride fastest across it, beyond just the avg power.
CoachComments: This is going to hurt for now - but it gives us a really important feedback point of how you're feeling creating race pace power in the new TT position - as well as a nice data point to build from. Let's see how you've responded to the strength work so far.

Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg

AthleteComments: *12/05/2018 Matti Rowe: Reppin' 185 on the squats now!  Core still weak as shit.  I think I figured out some of the lower back pain - I can full extend my right leg, but can't on my left - my left hamstring is super tight.  Going to work on that doubly hard.* *12/10/2018 Nate Wilson: Hey, so the single leg deadlift stuff is good for this - but stretching it is just as important. I like doing 60-90 sec each side of hamstring stretch in a door frame before bed. Like this... https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4kFBfgavg_o An additional core/hamstring/glute combo exercise you can add in, is this straight plank with alternating leg lifts. This usually challenges the hip flexor on the anterior side a bit as well. Do 15-20x each side depending on how you're feeling. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q*

Title: Z2 + Spin Ups
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min @ 210-230w, simple, clean. Include through the ride 4x30 sec @ 110+ rpm; not big power, just waking things up.
AthleteComments: *12/07/2018 Matti Rowe: OK, this was my first day on Zwift, and it was a freaking blast and I got carried away.  I actually went through 3 water bottles and bonked at the end.  I know it wasn't what you called for, but hopefully you'll excuse me for a little enthusiasm here and there, especially when riding indoors.* *12/10/2018 Nate Wilson: Nice! I will excuse for a bit of enthusiasm. I'm pumped you enjoyed Zwift  - it's definitely a game changer. That said - seeing how the week played out, I think we might need to exercise a bit more self control with it. It's a great way to get in some intensity here and there - but it should be an additive to the work we need to get done, not a subtraction. Like for Friday I'd say - no big deal of being time crunched and not being able to switch bikes. But realistically you could've done the work we had planned and just done it on the road bike. So not a huge thing here and there, but also don't want to let it turn into an avalanche effect, where over 4 weeks you're doing 4x a week that are just open smash on Zwift.*

Title: TT Strength Fdn (4x6)
WorkoutDescription: Easy warm up, then efforts: 3min build increasing power each min (290 < 320 < 350) - just a wake up. 4x6min @ 280-320w; 4-8 min recovery between, depending on sensation and terrain. Odd reps (1,3) @ 90-110 rpm; even reps (2,4) @ 60-70 rpm. Rest of the time comfortable pace.
AthleteComments: *12/07/2018 Matti Rowe: More Zwift.  Too time crunched to switch the TT bike onto the trainer, and it's still too icy to ride outside, and even if I could, I have too many mtgs today.*

Title: General Endurance + HC
WorkoutDescription: 3-3.5h general endurance. Go as you feel, but using HR as a handbrake to stay mostly < 150 bpm. In the final hour - 5x1min @ 320-350w, 110+ rpm / 1min recovery; prioritize cadence over power.
AthleteComments: *12/10/2018 Nate Wilson: Is this off your power meter or off the kickr meter? If it's off your meter, you're looking aerobically better than expected - 276w @ 5% HR drift, for 2:40. That's a super place to be for now. If it's from the kickr meter we need to get a bit more data to tease out difference between your meter and kickr meter, if at all.*

WorkoutDescription: Open day of general activity, enjoy it!
AthleteComments: *12/10/2018 Nate Wilson: I do have to say, I think this was the 4th day in a row that was perhaps a bit harder than necessary - not every day needs to be trying to avg 300w, especially for first week back training.*

Title: Sprint Work (4x stomps)
WorkoutDescription: Easy pace as your base (< 145 bpm), with efforts: 1x8min low Z3 (260-280w), 95+ rpm, then sprints: -2x15sec seated sprints in the little ring, only shifting when you're really running out of gear, keep upper body quiet. -4x20sec "stomps", done seated, in a big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, should only be hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so (adjust gear as necessary). Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min).
CoachComments: SPRINT EFFICIENCY
AthleteComments: *12/17/2018 Nate Wilson: Work more on the high cad on the initial tempo, more cadence than power. Go easier between sprints. This should be truly Z1 with maximal effort on sprint, than Z2.* *12/17/2018 Matti Rowe: Roger that*

Title: TT Strength (3x10)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, gear limited to the little ring, 105+ rpm where terrain allows. Then efforts: 3min build increasing power each min (290 < 320 <350) 3x10min 280-320w, 60-70 rpm / 6min recovery between. After, flush legs, then... 3x1min 320-350w, 110+ rpm / 1min recovery Cool down
AthleteComments: *12/17/2018 Nate Wilson: Efforts look good. HR pretty comfy. How'd they feel? Was this road or TT?* *12/17/2018 Matti Rowe: It felt harder than the heart rate showed, and it was on the TT bike on the trainer.*

Title: Active Recovery
WorkoutDescription: 45-90 min Z1 ride, HR < 130 bpm

Title: Z3 (2x15) - 1-3h based on time available
WorkoutDescription: 2x15min @ 300-330w; simple. One on climb (if weather allows), alt 2.5min seated / 30 sec standing. One on flat, 100+ rpm. Full recovery between.
CoachComments: OK to increase vol if you have time available.
AthleteComments: *12/16/2018 Matti Rowe: Drop outs in the last 1:20 on the Stages* *12/17/2018 Nate Wilson: If you're gonna be on trainer for 3h anyway I would warm up longer before getting into that first tempo - good to work on some power under fatigue rather than just getting into it right away. Good call to correct TSS.*

Title: Endurance w/ Surges
WorkoutDescription: Mostly Z2 pace - ok to be a bit more into Z3/stochastic if with a group. Space through the day 12-14 x 6-8 sec hard seated surges. These break up the day from being a long Z2 TT - add great neuromuscular stress to the ride. Focus on a quick transition from endurance pace, to acceleration, and back to endurance pace - with a quiet upper body and good leg speed.
CoachComments: Fuel @ 50-60 g of carbs per hour today to remind the gut of what we like.
AthleteComments: *12/17/2018 Matti Rowe: Felt amazing.* *12/17/2018 Nate Wilson: Sweet man, the aerobic capacity type stuff is looking better than it has in the past this time of year. Great power for the HR. I'm happy with it and we can maybe get into the higher intensities a bit earlier than planned. I may spice up this week just a hair to see how this diesel stuff is adding up in the other systems.*

Title: Z2 60-90 min + HC
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min @ 220-250w, nothing crazy. Include 5x3min @ 105+ rpm - Z2 effort.
AthleteComments: *12/21/2018 Matti Rowe: Got swamped.*

Title: 12/8/4 Cut Down
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up then efforts - ideally on climb: 12min progress from 300 < 350 - gradual progression. 8min race pace 4min race pace Full recovery between all efforts. Make the race pace efforts maximal, but with the goal of being maximal constant power, so more of a steady to neg split if anything, rather than a flash and fade. Cool down
AthleteComments: *12/21/2018 Matti Rowe: Man, I really wanted to ride outside today but Hads has her first Christmas concert and I can't miss that much work so I rode inside.  It was yeoman, but maybe not bad for the trainer.  I had loads of drop outs, so I just went with the Zwift file which reads about 20 watts lower than the Kickr.* *12/26/2018 Nate Wilson: No worries at all, you still got good work in. So this power file is from Zwift? Is there not also a file from your stages? In general it'd be good to have the stages file over the kickr file anyway - just so #s are as consistent to outside as possible.
