Title: Strength + Hip Drive Exercises
WorkoutDescription: Strength routine you've been doing - for squats and deadlift, keep it 2-3 sets of 12-15 reps on a weight that is moderately challenging, but where you finish each set feeling you could do 2-3 more reps. For squats - follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps, recover and reset between each jump rather than doing them as rapidly as possible. Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
CoachComments: Get this in 2x during the week; skip exercises you don't have equipment for.

Title: Muscular Recruitment Progressions

After do... 5x20 sec seated accelerations 110+ rpm / 40 sec recovery Cool down

Title: Sprint Work (6x stomps)
WorkoutDescription: Easy pace as your base (< 145 bpm), with efforts: 1x10min low Z3 (280-300w), 95+ rpm, then sprints: -2x15sec seated sprints in the little ring, only shifting when you're really running out of gear, keep upper body quiet. -6x20sec "stomps", done seated, in a big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, should only be hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so (adjust gear as necessary). Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min).

Title: Endurance / Tempo Day
WorkoutDescription: I'm writing this as though you'll be on the trainer - but the goal is a good day building aerobic capacity. So if you're able to be outside, volume is our friend, don't worry about the structured work - just get good endurance time in and accumulate 30-40 min of Z3 work as terrain dictates. If on trainer - mixed tempo work as follows: Warm up 5min ~300w (4min recovery) 5min build 260w < 360w (4min recovery) 10min ~300w (8min recovery) 10min alt 4min 300w / 1min 360w (8min recovery) 5min build 260w < 360w (4min recovery) 5min ~300w Cool down

Title: Strength (3x5 heavy squat, dl stays light) + Hip Drive Exercises
WorkoutDescription: We're entering a short high weight phase, you should warm up with a few of the core and isometric hip drive exercises before doing the squats and dead lift work. Squats - do 3 sets x 5 reps @ heavy weight, but only as much as you can do for 3 sets and with perfect form. If you feel form faltering, end the set early. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 10x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
CoachComments: Get this in 2x during the week; skip exercises you don't have equipment for.
AthleteComments: *01/07/2019 Nate Wilson: This heavy weight on the squats is the next step in building strength and in building explosive power under load - but it's also where it's easier for things to go wrong. So read heavy always as "heavy comfortable". If you come into a gym session feeling really beat up or tired, skip the heavy weight and just go through the motions on lighter weight.*

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Title: Broken VO2 (3 sets 6x40/20)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 12min Z3 progressive, increase power in 4 min chunks (280 < 310 < 340) Flush legs, then do some broken VO2 work. The goal of this isn't doing the max power across the set, but accumulating chunks of time at VO2 power (400-440w for now). Leave feedback on how this feels. 3 sets of 6x40 sec @ 400-440w / 20 sec recovery; 10min recovery between sets. Cool down
CoachComments: If nice weather and time in your day, it's ok to go longer today.

Title: Zwift Sensations
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min jump on Zwift and just ride with no structured objectives, enjoy.

Title: Z1/Recovery
WorkoutDescription: 30-60 min spin, HR < 120 bpm 5x30 sec one leg drills
AthleteComments: *01/24/2019 Matti Rowe: Feeling goddamn great* *01/28/2019 Nate Wilson: Nice, being able to freshen up with two days easy, then feel good after one day riding to essentially "open up" is a good sign I've always thought that you're working hard but not crossing the line of working really hard to where you can't freshen up and feel really good.*

Title: TT Strength Maint (4x5)
WorkoutDescription: Easy warm up, then a block (32 min total) of TT strength: 4x5min, 60-70 rpm, 300-330w / 4min, 90-100 rpm, 200-230w Cool down
AthleteComments: *01/28/2019 Nate Wilson: All looks pretty reasonable. Anything noteworthy on your sensation?* *01/28/2019 Matti Rowe: I think I was starting to get some lung congestion this day, because I felt kinda awful*

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Title: 12/8/4 Cut Down
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up then efforts - ideally on climb: 12min progress from 300 < 350 - gradual progression. 8min race pace 4min race pace Full recovery between all efforts. Make the race pace efforts maximal, but with the goal of being maximal constant power, so more of a steady to neg split if anything, rather than a flash and fade. Cool down
CoachComments: OK to go longer if you feel.
AthleteComments: *01/27/2019 Matti Rowe: Hacking up some phlegm today, so I felt a bit off, but gave in a nudge and wasn't completely terrible.* *01/28/2019 Nate Wilson: Glad we got these in. I didn't put them in so much as a "test" more just  it 's time for you to go out and hit the top end really hard once, and kind of shock the system to them and then it reminds your body what these are about for the time to come. The 4min is not bad @ 425w, it just looks a bit funny in that you really hit it hard that last minute, so it kind of raised up the avg last minute rather than sat pegged the whole time. But it's been awhile since doing anything of that sort of sustained intensity so it's hard to know what you'll be able to do. The 8 min I think is solid @ 407w considering it looks like you had some power drops. But I also think you only did 7 min not 8. So yeah, like you said maybe not your best day - hope you weren't feeling worse Sunday because if so I'd rather you have taken it a bit easier. But will go check that one now!*

Title: Baseline Aerobic Limit Ride (make meat of it ~3.5h)
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy warm up to get legs going. Then, goal is aerobic stress. High average power without going over Z3/Tempo (320w) Pick a route where you can stay fairly constant on the pedals, and minimize soft pedaling and coasting. Target a lot of time @ High Z2/Low Z3 (230-280w) 10min easy cool down to flush the effort. - Fueling for Sunday should look like a race day. Good carb rich dinner Saturday night, breakfast of mostly carbs but not such a huge meal that it sits heavy in your gut, dehydrates you, and draws blood from your legs (this relies on having a good dinner Sat night), then race like nutrition on the bike ~70 g of carbs per hour. You're gonna be riding pretty high up the energy burn!
AthleteComments: *01/28/2019 Nate Wilson: Cool, that looks pretty solid. 282w with no HR drift. You've done efforts in racing or training but other workouts that are maybe similar, but this is the best one of these out and out limit rides I think we've done. You had no HR drift, and HR was pretty comfortably in Z2 it looks like. So it'd be good to hear what you're feeling was here, but this looks really solid man. I feel this is some pretty big progress. Especially considering your peak 3h power over the past two years looks to be 279w from Gila in 2017. So to do more than that, for a bit longer, and no HR drift. Nice sign, nice sign!* *01/28/2019 Nate Wilson: Yeah I went back and looked at the day from Gila - it was 2017 when you hit the EB on the Mogollon stage. Your HR was a bit higher for similar power, but that's no surprise given we probably tapered in, and it was probably warmer, and you were touching the top end with a bit more frequency. The kind of adrenal boost you get on race day, makes that effort so much easier. So to knock it out in training, a bit more power, less HR drift, lower HR - great sign for January! I'm excited to start layering more intensity into these longer rides - that should be our focus over the next couple of months. We know now you can ride pretty hard for 3-4h, now we want to add in the riding fast sections.* *01/28/2019 Matti Rowe: It felt...weirdly effortless. At the 3.5 mark I wasn't really tired, I had just run out of food and Skratch (I brought 4 water bottles with me). I still had some hack in my lungs, but since I was basically in Z2 all day it wasn't forcing the sort of breathing that triggered anything. I expected to come through the door shattered, but I felt fine. Go figure.*

Title: Broken VO2 (2 sets 12x40/20)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 12min Z3 progressive, increase power in 4 min chunks (280 < 310 < 340) Flush legs, then do some broken VO2 work. The goal of this isn't doing the max power across the set, but accumulating chunks of time at VO2 power (400-440w for now). Leave feedback on how this feels. 2 sets of 12x40 sec @ 420-480w / 20 sec recovery; 8-10min recovery between sets. Cool down
AthleteComments: *01/29/2019 Matti Rowe: Good thing I was birthed from the pit of a fjord -  It was damn cold! My basement was tempting, but I like to do higher end work outside to try to maximize the quality. First set I felt a little rusty, but second set I really opened up and it felt comfortable ripping off 470ish for the ON. Forgot my heart rate meter in the pain cave, but I think I caught a good day.* *02/05/2019 Nate Wilson: Great, nice progress we're making here.*

AthleteComments: *02/05/2019 Nate Wilson: This all feeling good? More building you up rather than tearing you down and tightening hips with the heavy load? Plan to move to more light to mod weight in the next month or so - beginning of March at the latest.*

Title: TT Strength (2x20)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, gear limited to the little ring, 105+ rpm where terrain allows. Then efforts: 3min build increasing power each min (300 < 330 <360) 2x20min 300-330w, 60-70 rpm / 6min recovery between. After, flush legs, then... 3x1min 350-380w, 110+ rpm / 1min recovery Cool down
AthleteComments: *01/30/2019 Matti Rowe: Fuck me forgot my heart rate monitor again.  I felt like I was breathing through my nose though, but it was cold as shit again and I felt like an old Ford engine turning over in a Polar Vortex.* *02/05/2019 Nate Wilson: All good, way to get it in - improvement from these efforts last year.*

Title: HC Tempo
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min, relatively light ride with a bit of tempo work: 3x6min - first 4min 300-330w, 105+ rpm < 2min 350-380w, normal cadence Full recovery between

Title: Bookend Broken VO2 (30/30)
WorkoutDescription: Bookend ride today - two sets of identical effort, one done in the first 90 min, one done in the final 60 min. Between accumulate vertical gain, and time climbing @ 300-330w (if weather is no go for climbing, try to get ~35-40 min of 300-330w broken up on flats). Bookend sets: 10x30 sec @ 410-460w / 30 sec @ 280-340w Nail fueling in order to produce on the efforts.
CoachComments: 3-5h depending on time available.
AthleteComments: *02/03/2019 Matti Rowe: Short on time, so hit it a bit harder.  I went harder on Flag, but not all out, SS rather than tempo.  Fueling was on point, but maybe I should have waited a bit longer to do the last 30/30s since I ate a bar and then jumped right into it about 5 min later and though I felt energized it was harder to make the numbers pop over 440 on the ON.* *02/05/2019 Nate Wilson: Man it's crazy how far you've come in the past few years with the over/under work. This VO2 build hasn't really phased you at all it seems, which was kind of my hope - we can throw in some work to break up the winter, and start prepping the legs to higher force so that as we get to more LT type stuff it doesn't feel like you're pushing the pedals crazy hard. Flag looks mostly good, just looks like HR got quite high in the second half. Second set of 30/30's was down a bit, so yeah maybe just missing some pop. In a race scenario a thing to help here as well is a caffeine gel, like 100 mg, ~45-60 min before the final is going to start taking off. You can try this out in training on these kinds of rides and see how it feels.* *02/05/2019 Matti Rowe: Ooooo great idea!  I do respond well to those caffeine/carb gels.  I'll use those going forward!*

Title: Sensations Endurance (2-5h, depending on time available)
WorkoutDescription: Anywhere from 2-5h based on what you have time for - classical endurance day.
CoachComments: Mostly Z2 style - but some Z3/Z4 even on climbs is ok if feeling great.
AthleteComments: *02/04/2019 Matti Rowe: Short on time here, so I headed to Flag for some intervals.  To my surprise, I had legs. I was able to increase the power every rep.  I only started really giving er' in the last 5 minutes of the last rep.* *02/05/2019 Nate Wilson: All good, sounds fun!*

Title: Capacity LT (2x20)
WorkoutDescription: 2x20 min LT climbs as follows: 2min VO2 (near best effort) 3min Z3 (300-330w) 15 min Z4 (350-380w, control here on first rep and ok to do more on second rep if you feel good). 20+ min recovery between reps.
CoachComments: Volume isn't the concern today, anything from 2-3h total is fine. Do a 3-5 min Z3 progression to open up before the key efforts.
AthleteComments: *02/10/2019 Matti Rowe: Fi fÃ¦n! Hit this with race nutrition and I felt goddamn great. Hit an espresso gel with 100mg caffeine 10m before 2nd effort and I felt like I was on fire. Unfortunately, my rear skewer on the KICKR was getting loose and I actually fell off the bike midway through the second interval, so it was slightly interrupted but I finished hard.* *02/11/2019 Nate Wilson: Great work for the trainer man! Hope nothing got broken on body or bike!*

Title: VO2 Builder
WorkoutDescription: Smattering of efforts, with full recovery between, in this order: 6min Z3 progression (4min 300-330w < 2min 350-380w) 4m VO2 @ near max, but not so hard you don't think you could repeat (420ish is probably a solid mark); 5+ min recovery before starting 40/20s. 2 sets of 8 x 40 sec @ 420-470w / 20 sec recovery (these should be hard but repeatable, hold it there, don't push up); 6+ min recovery between sets. 2 x 90 sec aiming for same power you did the initial 4m at, 2m recovery between. Cool down
AthleteComments: *02/18/2019 Nate Wilson: Whoa! 470w on the 4min. Let's hope the power meter was right. This is definitely power that is doable for you - and you were going fast for going up Nelson. So yeah. Great job, responding well to the VO2 work I'd say.*

Title: TT DATA
WorkoutDescription: 11/15/18: 19:39, 335w, 169b, 87r, 41.7, 13.6k (training wheels, 63/Nelson TT loop) 2/15/19: 19:01, 347w, 167b, 87r, 42.9, 13.6k (training wheels, 63/Nelson loop)

Title: TT Marker - let's get a gauge on where you're at on the TT bike, that we can revisit
WorkoutDescription: 10-15 min easy spinning, start to mentally focus on the task ahead and center yourself - relaxed and ready to dig. 3-5 min in low tempo, reaching into high tempo 3min progression from low Z4 to high Z4 90 sec progression from high Z4 to mid Z5 Each of the above 3 is it's own step - do 2-3 min of easy spinning between each step. Then - do this course at TT race pace - https://www.strava.com/routes/16050083 Think about breaking down the course to ride fastest across it, beyond just the avg power.
CoachComments: This is going to hurt for now - but it gives us a really important feedback point of how you're feeling creating race pace power in the new TT position - as well as a nice data point to build from. Let's see how you've responded to the strength work so far.
AthleteComments: *02/18/2019 Nate Wilson: This is a really nice improvement from when we did this effort in November. You did 12 more watts, 347w vs 335w, and went 38 seconds faster. We both know wind conditions can be pretty variable in Boulder, so we don't have to place too much stake in the time, but power is power. And that is actually around the time savings I would expect. Nice progress, and a good spot for February. Let's keep grinding and try to add another 10-15 watts for the next time.*

Title: 3x8 TT Speed
WorkoutDescription: Progressive ramp from easy up to 230w. 1x6m Low Tempo (290-320w), 95+ rpm Flush legs. 3x8m @ RPE 8-9, make the recovery time however long it takes to ride back to the start point so that you do these all on the same stretch of road. Gauge these on RPE more than a given #, at least to start. First two reps, lock in on "hard, controlled", final rep try to get to a farther point down the road than the first 2 reps. Go as easy as you like home, don't think about power.
CoachComments: On the 3x8, think about position on the bike and riding slightly undulating power to maximize speed across the stretch of road you're on.
AthleteComments: *03/11/2019 Nate Wilson: That's great power to pretty much be 380w on all of these. How'd these feel? Would like to do at least one rep next time on a flatter course. Perhaps 63rd?* *03/11/2019 Matti Rowe: I allow myself some optimism after the workout. The power wasn't exactly flowing out of me, but it felt like I could have kept pushing that much longer if I had to.  As ever, it remains to be seen if that power and my narrower setup translates to speed with my mobile home width shoulder.*

Title: Baseline Aerobic Limit Ride (make meat of it ~4h)
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy warm up to get legs going. Then, goal is aerobic stress. High average power without going over Z3/Tempo (320w) Pick a route where you can stay fairly constant on the pedals, and minimize soft pedaling and coasting. Target a lot of time @ High Z2/Low Z3 (230-280w) 10min easy cool down to flush the effort. - Fueling for Sunday should look like a race day. Good carb rich dinner Saturday night, breakfast of mostly carbs but not such a huge meal that it sits heavy in your gut, dehydrates you, and draws blood from your legs (this relies on having a good dinner Sat night), then race like nutrition on the bike ~70 g of carbs per hour. You're gonna be riding pretty high up the energy burn!
AthleteComments: *03/11/2019 Nate Wilson: This looks good Matti. Last time we did it was about 6 weeks ago and you had a great one, 3h35m @ 282w with no drift. Today you went longer, 4h and a handful more wattage 287w. Still no drift. Looks good. How'd you feel? How'd you do with fueling?* *03/11/2019 Matti Rowe: I'm surprised this went well at all.  I got 5 hours of sleep the night before (Lars is a party animal), didn't make a point to really hit the carbohydrates the night before (Turns out my biggest ride window was Sat, not Sun) and when I started my heart rate immediately shot to 155 ish and I thought 'oh shit'.  But I ground it out, and ate my face off.  My back started giving me hell around the 3.5 hour mark, but oddly loosened back up again after I took down a gel with caffeine.*

Title: VO2 Builder
WorkoutDescription: Smattering of efforts, with full recovery between, in this order: 20min upper Z3 @ 320-350w 4m VO2 @ near max, but not so hard you don't think you could repeat (420ish is probably a solid mark); 5+ min recovery before starting 40/20s. 2 sets of 8 x 40 sec @ 420-470w / 20 sec recovery (these should be hard but repeatable, hold it there, don't push up); 6+ min recovery between sets. 2 x 90 sec aiming for same power you did the initial 4m at, 2m recovery between. Cool down
AthleteComments: *03/10/2019 Matti Rowe: No top end, probably bc I could barely eat after yesterdayâ€™s ride. Upshot is I just rode, which makes me happier than not riding.* *03/11/2019 Nate Wilson: Awesome, glad you got out and enjoyed the ride. Not being able to eat certainly is not going to help that VO2 power. It's been a really stacked week to, with a lot of intensity for one week. So no problem missing this.*

Title: SFR Maint (5x3)

Title: VO2: 4x4
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 12min build increasing power every 4min (280 < 320 < 360) 4x4min VO2 / 4min recovery - goal is maximal power you can do across the set without dropping as you go. So first couple should be hard but in control. Cool down
CoachComments: Feel it out, would rather be a bit conservative and chomping at the bit for Sunday than to view this as a "test" workout - it's not.
AthleteComments: *03/18/2019 Nate Wilson: Dropped a bit - but overall really solid across the set! And looks like this was backed up with good legs on the weekend. It's nice when we're seeing good #s and racing and that translates to good competition performance - not always the case!* *03/18/2019 Matti Rowe: Thanks - yeah I didn't have fantastic legs and I was on the trainer but I left feeling like it was 'Helt OK'.*

AthleteComments: *03/18/2019 Nate Wilson: OK well that 385w on the middle one was a bit harder than necessary. Wanted that to be more like a bite at 30-40 min TT pace, rather than 8 min hard effort. But - flip to that is I'm thrilled to see the power is doable on flat grade. If you can do it on that stretch of 66 you can do it anywhere!* *03/18/2019 Matti Rowe: My bad. I didnâ€™t try for that power, I just thought it was race pace and went off sensation.*

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Title: Air Force RR - 4th!
WorkoutDescription: 70g of carbs per hour, and being smart with your energy.
CoachComments: https://www.coloradocycling.org/results/road#year=2019&eventId=2409&resultsetId=29857
AthleteComments: *03/18/2019 Matti Rowe: 4th place!  Â¯\_(ãƒ„)_/Â¯. At 4 gels, 1.5 Honey Stinger, and 2 Skratch bottles.  Maybe I overdid it, but I was fairly bursting with energy on the last climb.* *03/18/2019 Nate Wilson: Awesome job Matti - that's a great way to open the season! I always think it's hard racing up at the Air Force. The higher altitude is really sneaky. For being at altitude and how high intensity this day is I'd rather see you eat a bit more than under eat and just survive. 377w for 10.5 min @ the tail end @ 2100 m elevation is solid. And when you spend 40+ minutes at Z4, Z5, and Z6 - all at 7000+ feet - it's a much higher carb 2.25 hours than if it's just 2.25 hours Z2. So good to compensate with fuel, and good to have these habits in place for longer races to come.*

Title: JMSR St. 1
WorkoutDescription: Aiming for 70g of carbs per hour, and being smart with your energy. A good finish for you if you manage yourself well leading up to it!
AthleteComments: *04/08/2019 Nate Wilson: I'll be interested to hear how you felt hear. I thought it was a pretty solid result for your first race at this level - especially considering you were pretty sick the week leading in. HR didn't get too crazy as they day went on - so it looks like you did alright with hydration, but let me know how it seemed from your end. Looks like you were getting a ton of power drops. These numbers seem low and you can see in the file there are an unrealistic number of drops. Will increase this one to 320 TSS. I also forgot to adjust your FTP for sea level.* *04/09/2019 Matti Rowe: I almost got dropped immediately after neutral.  My nose was streaming snot and it was down pouring and I was shivering uncontrollably.  I just ate and hid all day.  My nose stopped.  In the last hour I felt like I could dig.  I couldn't get in a good position before the climb kicked off, so I just turboed hard and picked off about 30 people into the finish.*

Title: JMSR St. 2
WorkoutDescription: Repeat eating/drinking habits from St. 1!
AthleteComments: *04/08/2019 Nate Wilson: Increasing TSS again. This week when you have downtime at the office leave notes on how you felt and what you did well / poorly.* *04/09/2019 Matti Rowe: I felt great today actually.  The nose was normal.  I had energy.  I ate and hid.  I was tempted once to go in a break, but was intimidated by 117 miles distance, so I just sat in. Team plan was to lead out our sprinter, so I got to the front a few times near the end with our train and tried to pull, but honestly the power and flow of the pack was really hard to navigate. Rolled in with the peloton.*

Title: TT - Warm Up
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 12min ramp from easy to low Z3 (just hitting 320ish watts by the last min) 3min easy 4x30 hard / 30 easy (progression from 350 < 375 < 400 < 425, each progressive 30) 3min easy 90 sec race pace Flush legs, roll to the line and go. Sensation is really going to be your best guide today - stay below 440w the first 3min, then check in with adrenaline and go from there! 15-20 min cool down while sipping a recovery drink, and then legs up for tomorrow!

Title: TT - Devil's Den
AthleteComments: *04/08/2019 Nate Wilson: Power wise I think you did ok here. The 8 min chunk of the climb (first climb) was pretty even, but I do think you should've done less the first part and more the second part. Here's the #s - first 4 min are ~440w avg and 5% avg grade. Next 4min are 430w avg and 8% avg grade - want a bit more differential there to do more power where it's steeper. But overall good even split. Looks like you lost the pace a bit over the top. Just nitpicking there though - could've held on a bit more into the downhill before backing off - overall good. That last 90 sec is totally brutal, good job to dig in. HR sure was responding. 20 more watts than last year - which I know wasn't a very good day but overall good improvement and in a race with arguably harder two days prior this year!* *04/09/2019 Matti Rowe: I bled in the last 3 minutes because I went too hard in the first 5. That said, I had good sensations in warm up so I thought I was on a good day and maybe could hold something special.  Instead I just held on. Still beat my time last year by 1:40!*

Title: Easy AM Spin
WorkoutDescription: 30-60 min easy spin to keep the legs loose. 3-5 x 20-30 sec @ 120+ rpm; not big power, but helping clear the legs.

Title: Crit
WorkoutDescription: Warm up well and be ready to rip. Light gears out of the corners to save the legs for when you need to big dog!
AthleteComments: *04/08/2019 Nate Wilson: Notoriously one of the hardest crits in the US. So really a huge step to make it through this one - really a huge week overall Matti. Looking forward to hearing your story of it.* *04/09/2019 Matti Rowe: More than anything, I'm proud of this day.  With 10 laps to go, I was in the box, but I wanted to finish this goddamn crit so bad so I just bled and bled and held on.*

AthleteComments: *04/15/2019 Nate Wilson: Awesome, TT work is all looking good at the moment. Letâ€™s keep the ball rolling straight into Gila with this. And guessing you felt pretty freshened up from JMSR at this point?* *04/15/2019 Matti Rowe: I did! Felt great even though it was cold AF*

Title: Cobb Lake (TBD)
AthleteComments: *04/13/2019 Matti Rowe: 3rd! First P12 podium ever!* *04/15/2019 Nate Wilson: Thatâ€™s awesome Matti! Way to make it happen. Your race craft and engine are really coming into their own. Howâ€™d the finish play out? Think thereâ€™s anything you couldâ€™ve done better?* *04/15/2019 Matti Rowe: On the 6th lap it got hard and everyone sat up going into a turn. I felt OK and jumped, railed the turn, and only 3 other guys followed. We worked together but the peloton was closing hard on the gravel and the rest of the guys could barely pull. I made a call to push hard so we stayed away but knew that would fuck me for the finish. I managed to beat one of the guys to the line, but Dewar and Selker were too punchy. In hindsight maybe I should have tried to jump them in the rotation earlier when they seemed worked?* *04/15/2019 Nate Wilson: Yeah that's a tough one - always that gamble between you want the break to stay away and you'd take 3 or 4 over getting caught by the field. But then figuring out from there how you can increase your odds of winning if you know you're likely not to just taking the group to the line. If they're truly dead weight it's good sometimes to try and dump them early, as long as you're not worried that they have a strong team back in the field that might then rip the chase. If they're not total dead weight, but they're just on the limit a bit - then yeah best thing is find a moment when you're at the back, and they're on the front - sometimes you need to find a way to sit out a turn, or sort of change your position within the group through a corner - to target the guy you want to get rid of. Wait until they pull and they're almost just about pulling off and then just whack it as hard as you can around them - swing to the other side of the road from the back so that they can't just be straight on the wheel.*

Title: 15/4 TT Workout (Lefthand)
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min progressive warm up building from easy to Z2 10min low Z3, 95+ rpm Then some TT efforts on lefthand. Start at lefthand/36 do 15min at TT pace where RPE is strong, but in control. Immediately flip it at start descending, ride in sticks where comfortable - power is easy, but keep leg speed 100+ rpm when pedaling. At bottom, turn around, ride 30 sec active recovery, then do 1x4min race pace - really open up the throttle on this one, stay in sticks for 3min then it's ok to get out and drive the last min if you feel you'll do more power that way. Easy spin home.
AthleteComments: *04/23/2019 Nate Wilson: This looks solid - it's good seeing 360w be pretty doable on that 15.*

Title: Capacity LT
WorkoutDescription: 90 min Z2 (below 240w) with a 15 sec acceleration every 20 min (4x total). Second half: 2x20 min LT climbs as follows: 2min VO2 (near best effort) 2min Z3 (300-330w) 16 min Z4 (350-380w) 15+ min recovery between. 2.5-3.5h total.
AthleteComments: *04/21/2019 Matti Rowe: Couldn't hack it - Bad legs.  Trying to get over it.* *04/21/2019 Matti Rowe: Looking back, power, heart rate was OK through first effort, but then fell off hard. I only had 2 bottles during the entire ride, I think I fell off a dehydration cliff.* *04/23/2019 Nate Wilson: Yeah that all is reasonable. And often riding in the afternoon it can just be a weird fueling cycle. Where you don't necessarily feel hungry, but you kind of working out at a different time of day and in the back half of the ride you fall off. We know you're fit - not every day has to be a diamond.*

Title: Flag Rip
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, into a few min of tempo to get loose. Flag rip to amphitheater. Cool down
AthleteComments: *04/26/2019 Matti Rowe: I broke 13 minutes for the first time. I've always wanted to. That said, I shouldn't have done this. Hadley is sick, and I was feeling something and I should have taken the day off or done a recovery ride. I'm admitting this because it's not something you can see from the data, but it matters, and it was a dumb decision to let ego prevail rather than being smart. Miraculously, I feel 1000x better today.  Hopefully that holds. But I want to remind myself (and you) that this was a dumb decision that could have made me sick right before my A race. Idiot. Still have a lot to learn.* *04/29/2019 Nate Wilson: Well, like you said - got a bit lucky and looking at the rest of the week it looks like it panned out ok! But that's experience talking to notice that it really was unnecessary. In the future you could've just done this tempo to keep the legs going but not really put yourself into a spot of danger. That said - great form check to go that quick!*

Title: Long General + Torque Accels
WorkoutDescription: Not a huge smasher day, just a general endurance day in the saddle; mostly Z2 - but would be great to go with a group and be a bit more stochastic. Want this day to feel long, but easy overall - really conscious of carb and fluid (bottle every 45-60 min) intake to minimize deficit of this ride. Every 20 min do a 20 sec seated acceleration, alternating one high torque, one high cad. High Torque = shift to a bigger gear each time you hit 85 rpm until out of gears High Cad = 110+ rpm, leg speed all the way
AthleteComments: *04/29/2019 Nate Wilson: Nice man, looks comfortable all day. This race will be tough, but you know it well and you're going in with awesome form! Keep to the fundamentals and you'll have a good week.*

Title: Mogollon
WorkoutDescription: Eat, hydrate. Stay on point from the circuits onward. Don't be crazy, and always be saving energy as much as possible, but just keep the eyes open, and the skin sensitive to what's happening with the wind.
AthleteComments: *05/01/2019 Matti Rowe: When it was time to go hard, I was just empty. Fueling on point, I was just a shell of myself. Hope Iâ€™m not cooked from those ATL spikes earlier this year. I'm guessing I walked too much of a tight rope with weight in the week leading up to this/allergies.* *05/09/2019 Nate Wilson: Sounds like you nailed it with saying you walked a bit of a tight rope with the weight. Glad to see though it didn't just get worse from there - did great to rally and have a good rest of week. Do you feel like you did anything after this stage that brought you out of the hole? Just ate a bunch of carbs and got up on fluids?* *05/09/2019 Matti Rowe: I ate a bunch for sure, but honestly I think I was kinda hanging on after the Flag Rip since last Thursday almost made me sick.  I just had weird sensations and maybe, like JMSR, the body just kind of snapped out of it after the first day.*

Title: Inner Loop
WorkoutDescription: This one can start fast and hard, especially if the wind comes out to play. So get a good warmup in so you're not caught with your pants down. If you need to, put gels down in the first hour, so you don't make it to 1h in without having eaten anything. This is an easy stage to make a hole in the beginning, and if you make that hole then end up in the break right when the pace comes off, then you never get out of the hole.
AthleteComments: *05/05/2019 Matti Rowe: Legs came back.* *05/09/2019 Nate Wilson: Yeah it was a hard pace for sure over the top of the first KOM to go 5 min @ 395w. Last climb doesn't look too bad mostly 320-330w. That climb is almost never super huge power as you can really draft but also just usually doesn't feel good if you got at all behind on fueling. Good news is the climbs in the pro field are avg 320-330w for you. That's because you are a lot lighter in the past these would've been 350+ climbs for you at this pace. So that's an awesome job on your end, but now it's just finding the balance of where you lose the strength or don't have the fuel in the tank.*

Title: TT
WorkoutDescription: Don't need to go nuts on the warmup as you're pretty open after the first two days, but it may take awhile to get open. Ideal is to ride to the TT course (light 20-30min), then do just enough effort once there to open up. 1x3-5min low race pace, and 2-3 x short accelerations. Once you feel the legs pop open that's enough.
CoachComments: Sensation will likely be a more powerful guide than power today: First climb = hard but controlled, in the bars as much as possible Up to speed ASAP into the downhill, and then goal is "aero" not power production Rollers both directions, driving hard over the top up to speed, then floating slightly into the next. Last big climb out = taste blood, taste blood over the top and up to 35mph. Get small, any time you feel the speed drop, you give it 20 sec HARD to get it back up. Grade drops out the last 1-2k and you've got to just big dog it and get ugly, STAY SMALL!!
AthleteComments: *05/03/2019 Matti Rowe: 36:42, 42nd. No file - I forgot to hit start on the Garmin. It was a shit show/nightmare warm up.  I went to get my bike checked at the jig and basically had to overhaul the cockpit with 30 minutes to my start time. Dropped bars 3 inches, moved the sticks back 7 cm, tilted the sticks down. That said, didn't panic, paced well, beat my time last year by 20 seconds.* *05/09/2019 Nate Wilson: Damn, I'm sorry that the cockpit ended up being so far off. I'm surprised the sticks would've not been within 7 cm?! Did the bike feel totally different? Honestly this is something I can help you with in the future. Probably I should've just said I'd come to your place and in 20 min we could have it all good to go. Nice job to still go faster than last year!* *05/09/2019 Matti Rowe: Yeah, it felt like a different bike, but at least I maintained the width on the sticks and stayed narrow which was probably the biggest change we made last year. That probably helped because I think the watts were a bit down.*

Title: 30min AM Spin
WorkoutDescription: Light spin to shake out yesterday's efforts and keep the legs moving. Be pro tour, lounge at the cafe. If it's legitimately hot don't lounge too long, don't need that.

Title: Crit
WorkoutDescription: Good warmup and cool down. This is a great stage to just find a comfortable spot in the field, focus on light gears up the climb in the middle of the race - and then ratchet down and fight in the last 10 laps. Be really aware of getting hydration in as it can certainly impact you for the final day.
AthleteComments: *05/05/2019 Matti Rowe: Crashed with 4 to go, got same time as lead group.* *05/09/2019 Nate Wilson: Ah shoot, hopefully not too banged up! Did you flat in the middle or something? Wattage was not that big for you here 288 NP. For comparison in 2016 in the 1/2 it was 304 NP. So not night and day, but theoretically this is a higher power field doing the pros - might just be you smoothing out in the field a bit and being more economical. All positive!* *05/09/2019 Matti Rowe: Yep, I had a flat midway through, took a free lap. I found a good flow that felt pretty comfortable and wasn't working nearly as hard as I was in the field last year.*

Title: Fuck 'em up
WorkoutDescription: This day notoriously starts pretty dang hard in the pros as the break gets established. You've got the legs for - a lot of it is just the self talk to remind yourself that everyone's fighting and that it hurts for everyone. You know how to fuel for this!
AthleteComments: *05/05/2019 Matti Rowe: Made the front group on the first climb to the ruins. Popped on the second. Finished. Iâ€™m proud, man.* *05/09/2019 Nate Wilson: Nice job man, this is a massive day. Do you have a general recollection of what you ate and drank on this stage? That climb out of the turnaround is always where the stage really starts opening up. Always is hard the first 5 min of that climb, ton of guys get dropped, then usually settles in a bit.* *05/09/2019 Matti Rowe: 5 bottles, 4 gels, a waffle and a bar leading up to the turnaround climb.  Not great but decent?*

Title: HVILE - Matti - Note Fueling Reminder for the future
WorkoutDescription: Can spin easy if you like - but not a must.
AthleteComments: *05/06/2019 Matti Rowe: Had more time to reflect on Gila.  One noticeable thing was that power was down. Wasn't a total killer since weight was lower this year than last, but it's dawning on me for the future that once you're approaching the final runway to a stage race it's stupid to play those deficits so hard. Power tends to go away and you don't have that reserve to tap into when you're 5 days in.  I think I've gotten away with it a few times this year on one-day races but if I roll into a JMSR or a Gila I started super hungry I'm going to pay a price. Obvious shit, I'm sure, but I'm putting this down here as much for myself for the future.* *05/09/2019 Nate Wilson: Hey I think that's really good feedback. I also went and looked back at all your weight logs for the past 8 weeks or so and you were pretty much 75-76 kg running into JMSR and at JMSR. Then after JMSR you started dropping a bit more to 74 kg; may be that just put a bit more strain on the whole build leading up to Gila and on Gila itself - especially like you're saying if in the days leading in you were clutching super hard to keep the weight there. Once you get within 3 days of the race it's definitely important to be conscious of having the glycogen stores topped up.*

WorkoutDescription: Your day, enjoy

Title: Strength (2x12 maintenance squat, dl stays light) + Hip Drive Exercises
WorkoutDescription: We're entering a short high weight phase, you should warm up with a few of the core and isometric hip drive exercises before doing the squats and dead lift work. Squats - do 2 sets x 12 reps @ light to moderate weight. Goal is keeping the movement pattern familiar but starting to give way to increased intensity on the bike. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
CoachComments: Get this in 2x during the week; skip exercises you don't have equipment for.

Title: Olde Stage Strava
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up Do a 10 min Z3 on lefthand or 36, build to Z4 the last 2min Then head over to Olde Stage - do a max strava effort on the segment from Lefthand to top. Cool down
AthleteComments: *05/20/2019 Nate Wilson: Cool, probably a better more tempered opener than what I had with the strava max thing.*

Title: Morgul TT
WorkoutDescription: Opener as you feel with time available
AthleteComments: *05/18/2019 Matti Rowe: Over a minute faster than last year. Fucking stoked to be headed the right direction* *05/18/2019 Matti Rowe: Self-criticism though Avg heart rate was pretty low for the effort - 158.  I think I could have bled more on this one.* *05/20/2019 Nate Wilson: Power wise this is awesome progress as well. 372w for 17 min. Back earlier in the year when we were doing TT efforts on our 63/Nelson/75 TT box you did one in Dec that was ~20 min @ 335w and then another in Feb that was 347w. So similar duration and another 25w - that's fitness baby! Looking at HR I don't think you should read into it. If you look at that graph it looks like it was just wrong. Like either battery dying or maybe picking up sometime and then just dropping and not reading right others. Any time the graph really shows that weird boxy line for HR I don't place too much value on it. Also sorry I didn't have this in the schedule. I guess I didn't really realize that when you weren't going to Seattle that meant you were probably gonna do the TT. Probably would've changed the lead in a bit, but looks like this worked fine. Send me some photos of you in the TT if you find some.* *05/20/2019 Nate Wilson: I also think you did a better job of applying power across the course this year and didn't drop so much on the downhills. On the downhills being a bit heavier helps, but i also think we need to get you more aero before you're really getting advantage of your weight - looking forward to playing with this perhaps a bit more this summer.*

Title: Morgul RR - Femte Plass!! (5th place!)
AthleteComments: *05/19/2019 Matti Rowe: Got in the early break of 7 which went straight from the gun and we rolled it.  Had a teammate in the break with me and he attacked on the 4th lap and stuck it for the W.  I'd like to say I could have followed, not that I should have, but I didn't have the punch he had. Paced it in with another guy and kept the field at bay for 5th.  A little pissed I didn't snag 4th because he was gassed and I felt good, but he had a wicked punch to him and even though I tried to surprise him a few times, I couldn't shake him and he just blew past me on the last part of the wall. I know it's not really in my wheelhouse, but damn a bit more punch could go a long way.* *05/20/2019 Nate Wilson: Man, this is really awesome. I remember a few years ago we were just trying to figure out how to get you stay in the field in this race. Now you're in the break and top 5! I also think this version of the course is harder, there's just no recovery. Yeah the punch up the wall for the finish is always tough for guys like you and me. I remember being in that spot a few times on this race and feeling like I could roll another lap fairly hard but I just could never do the 700w 30 sec or whatever it would be for me. That said, it's something to never give up on - and you will keep getting better at it. Where did you try and ditch him? I always think over the top of climbs is one of the best place, because everyone is just suffering on the climb but mentally prepared to do so and they're telling themselves just make it to the downhill and it'll get easy, and if you can just whack it super hard over the top and even come from a couple lengths back so you come back with some momentum sometimes you can just beat them mentally and they can't even try to get on the wheel. Hey, nice job. Enjoy the family time this week!*

Title: FL 20-27th - Will Have Bike - Open Sensations Block
Open Week
WorkoutDescription: Enjoy time on the bike, make your own schedule. Ok to mix in a bit of intensity as you like - but I think it would be good to avoid maximal intensity, especially maximal sustained intensity that last longer than 5 min. Want to get a bit of mental freshness back and get away from the being pinned @ LT feeling, at least for this week. We go back to building aerobic base when you're back! Day's off are ok - prioritize family time. Get body work in, but ok to move those days around.

Title: TT Strength (3x10) + HC Z4

AthleteComments: *06/04/2019 Nate Wilson: All looks pretty on the money. Cadence was right on 100 on the 90s, try and rev the leg speed a bit more on these. It's about tapping the fast twitch fibers under fatigue, and being able to switch into that after the strength work. Anything noteworthy on sensations?* *06/04/2019 Matti Rowe: I felt good!*

Title: SFR + 4' Capacity

CoachComments: OK to extend vol if you have time/desire

Saw this was an AM ride - pre-breakfast by chance? Or feel you went exceptionally on carbs at dinner the night prior?* *06/04/2019 Matti Rowe: I didn't have time for breakfast so I just mixed a bottle of Skratch and drank that figuring it would be enough.  Dinner the night before was chicken and salad, so I guess I just tapped myself.*

Title: Rhythm Change Tempo + PoP + 8min Z4 climb
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 10 min alternating 4.5 min 300-330w / 30 sec 450-500w Flush legs, then do 1 sets of: 20 sec hard (40 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 40 sec hard (20 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 20 sec hard Flush legs and do 1x8 min TT pace on a climb (not a gut buster 8 min, I'd say ~400w) Cool down
CoachComments: On these short efforts the goal is to go hard but feel good. So make them hard but in control - all based off on sensation. Never be tasting blood or feeling like you have to self talk to keep the power up.
AthleteComments: *07/02/2019 Nate Wilson: All good, power looks solid on the 8' - did it feel in control or did you feel like you kind of lost it at the end there? Good VAM!* *07/02/2019 Matti Rowe: I totally lost it at the end, but since I was close to the end of Linden, I finished it.*

Title: Eldora TT
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 12min ramp from easy to low Z3 (just hitting 320ish watts by the last min) 3min easy 4x30 hard / 30 easy (progression from 350 < 375 < 400 < 425, each progressive 30) 3min easy 90 sec race pace Flush legs, roll to the line and go. Sensation is really going to be your best guide here, given the altitude. You should go out the first 3-4 min at a pace that feels hard but in control, then coming out of the turnaround try to just really focus on being small and maximizing the speed for the effort, once you hit the climb it's all just staying relaxed and getting the power out - slowly squeeze the trigger down, you've got ~10 min of solid work here. 15-20 min cool down while sipping a recovery drink, and then legs up for tomorrow!
AthleteComments: *06/29/2019 Matti Rowe: Fjerde plass!  I think I should have brought my TT bike, because I got shredded on the flat section and couldn't get comfortable or put much power down. The shelf road climb was disappointing but OK.  I didn't have great power, and Jameson Ribbens, the 3rd place guy and my teammate, caught me (30 sec behind) and put in a dig, so I figured I'd try and hold on and fight.  I leaked 30 seconds to him up the climb in the end, but fought pretty hard, at least according to my heart rate.* *07/02/2019 Nate Wilson: Nice not a bad result at all! Yeah that's an interesting one - I guess by time ~50-55% of the course would be better on a TT bike. So it's a tough call. In the WT they'd probably do a bike change for this. I guess it just comes down to being comfortable climbing on the TT bike. Next year this would be a fun one to do some specific efforts to prepare for like just doing some hard climbing on TT bike and seeing how it feels. If I just saw your power for the shelf climb I'd think it wasn't bad - 360w for 10 min at that elevation is pretty solid for you. But yeah you took it into the climb for 375w the first 5 min and then clearly dropped off. I wonder if you could've gotten more avg for the 10 min climbs as a whole if you'd gone into the red less at the bottom?*

Title: New Glarus RR
AthleteComments: *07/15/2019 Matti Rowe: 5th place.  I wanted the podium, so I'm a bit deflated. Frontier decided not to bring my bike along to Madison, so I had to borrow my sister's boyfriends bike, which was too small (54cm) but very dope Trek Edomondo. Breaks couldn't get away, and I just followed wheels for 3 laps, but attacked the uphill finish on the 3rd trying to get away.  I got a gap, but the guys that could stay with me were too fucked after the effort to work so we got caught. On the final uphill finish the biggest team in the race attacked.  I closed the gap and attacked over him, but started flooding, and then 4 other dudes just danced past me. Wanted more, but it was a hell of a time.  I don't think I've raced in anything hotter before - it was 95F and humid AF. THANK GOD my sister agreed to be rad and work the neutral feed for 3 hours in the heat - just want she wanted to do for her birthday right?? Anyway, it's Monday, I feel rested.* *07/15/2019 Nate Wilson: Way to make lemonade out of lemons! That sounds like a small bike for ya! Bummer about not making the podium - sounds like you really gave it a solid go. Maybe a bit over aggressive in the final and could've waited later to really make the all in push for the line, but my guess is that was a good gamble.*

Title: Strength (2x12 maintenance squat, dl stays light) + Hip Drive Exercises
WorkoutDescription: We're entering a short high weight phase, you should warm up with a few of the core and isometric hip drive exercises before doing the squats and dead lift work. Squats - do 2 sets x 12 reps @ light to moderate weight. Goal is keeping the movement pattern familiar but starting to give way to increased intensity on the bike. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
CoachComments: Get this in 2x during the week; skip exercises you don't have equipment for.

Steady Z4 @ 340-380w 3. Alt 1 min @ 320-350w / 1min @ 380-410w 4. Steady Z4 @ 340-380w Recovery time as needed between the 4x8. Cool down

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling + Body Work
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.
CoachComments: After video, do: 10x body weight squats 5x single leg squats 10-15x pushups 20-30x sit ups

Title: TT Marker
WorkoutDescription: 10-15 min easy spinning, start to mentally focus on the task ahead and center yourself - relaxed and ready to dig. 3-5 min in low tempo, reaching into high tempo 3min progression from low Z4 to high Z4 90 sec progression from high Z4 to mid Z5 Each of the above 3 is it's own step - do 2-3 min of easy spinning between each step. Then - do this course at TT race pace - https://www.strava.com/routes/16050083 Think about breaking down the course to ride fastest across it, beyond just the avg power.
CoachComments: This is going to hurt for now - but it gives us a really important feedback point of how you're feeling creating race pace power in the new TT position - as well as a nice data point to build from. Let's see how you've responded to the strength work so far.
AthleteComments: *08/01/2019 Matti Rowe: I had a headwind on 63rd to Niwot and then basically different versions of a tailwind on the way back, so I don't know if the time is complete BS, 7 watts makes that much of a difference, or I'm just more aero.* *08/05/2019 Nate Wilson: Probably a little of everything! More power is always good regardless and the #s would say that you are more aero from the testing we did.* *08/05/2019 Nate Wilson: 46.4 kph avg is really fast even for fast weather conditions, and you hit all directions so it can't really be prevailing tail wind unless the wind really changes like mid way through a 17 min run which is possible but seems unlikely. Looking forward to seeing if we're on the mark come SSSR!*

AthleteComments: *09/02/2019 Nate Wilson: All good here.*

Title: Body Work (mixed hips/glutes/core)
WorkoutDescription: Warm up / activation with Founders pose - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vOgxWp0WyiI 7 way hips (10-15 reps each way): https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iLTBIaHU5iw 10-15x push up 2 sets x 15 reps body weight squats (slow, and only as deep as you can control the motion) Bird dog plank (2 sets x 10 reps each side, no foam roller under knees) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wiFNA3sqjCA 15-20x glute bridge (focus on digging heels into ground and pulling towards glutes, to engage hamstrings) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=usDCGz_Vv2k Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo

Title: TT Opener
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min easy spin with efforts; can do as recon on TT course if already up there: 1x5min ~300w, 60-70 rpm, lock in on quiet body in the position 1x5min @ race pace RPE (remember this is 30 min, not 5 min) 1x30 sec over threshold by feel - but not at 30 sec max Full recovery between all efforts.
AthleteComments: *09/02/2019 Nate Wilson: Is doing openers today and recovery Friday how we had it originally or was that a change you made?*

Title: Z1/Recovery
WorkoutDescription: 30-60 min spin, HR < 120 bpm 5x30 sec one leg drills

Title: St. 1 TT
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 12min ramp from easy to low Z3 (just hitting 280ish watts by the last min) 3min easy 3 min progressive (300 < 330 < 360) 3min easy 90 sec progressive (370 < 400 < 430) Flush legs, roll to the line and go. We'll talk about pacing. 15-20 min cool down while sipping a recovery drink, and then legs up for tomorrow!
AthleteComments: *08/31/2019 Matti Rowe: Took 30 sec off my PR.  BBS said .25ish CdA, so that's a nice improvement over a Bus. Power was low, but I was on a different power meter (the dual sided) since my normal one inexplicably shit the bed (it's 6 years old so maybe it finally kicked it). Not really happy. I wanted sub 27. Just feels like I was never made to TT fast.* *09/01/2019 Matti Rowe: I got 8/29. That helped me sleep easier. http://www.bikesteamboat.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/SSSR-Stage-1-TT.pdf* *09/02/2019 Nate Wilson: Hey man, I know perhaps we hoped for bigger progress. But looking at the results I think this was great, one of - probably the best - best TT's you've ever done in this field, on a flat no hiding constant power course. We're maybe not making 10% leaps and bounds, but we're chipping away at progress.*

Title: Over-Under Z4's - 3x8
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, then efforts: 5 min progressive Z3 build 280w to 380w (+25w per min) 3x8 min as follows... 30 sec @ 400-450w / 30 sec @ 270-320w (x2) 4 min @ 350-380w 30 sec @ 400-450w / 30 sec @ 270-320w (x2) Cool down

Title: Stars in Your Eyes
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, concluding with a 10min progressive tempo building from 280w to 360w (last 2min @ 360w). 2 sets of: 20 sec hard (40 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 40 sec hard (20 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 20 sec hard (3min recovery between sets) Read "hard" for these as, hard but in control - essentially what feels good for that effort. Should be pushing the top end but never really telling yourself "hold on", "dig deep", "more power".

Title: Thunderbird RR
AthleteComments: *09/08/2019 Matti Rowe: Sjuende plass og vi vant!* *09/09/2019 Matti Rowe: I'm happy with this one.  It showcased everything I've become as a racer. I attacked early alone.  Not because I thought it would stick, but because I didn't want to get dropped with the rest of the field when Gavin Mannion did, and I thought If I got up the road he might be willing to work with me. That happened. Three other guys made it with Gavin.  After a lap, I couldn't hang. The field was shattered and I joined the chase group.  I got dropped from that. But I kept eating. And I kept using others to stay in the game. And then my legs came back. And guys that dropped me in the first two laps I blew by. And I kept eating and getting stronger, and other guys lights went out.  I even gave someone a gel because I had brought more than enough food. My teammates and I attacked a few other guys to secure the minor places, and ultimately I wasn't in the roulette wheel that finally broke a few others. But I still finished 7th. And my family was there. Hell of a way to end the year.  Jeg har allered ild i magen min mot neste Ã¥r!*

Title: Strength (2x12 maintenance squat, dl stays light) + Hip Drive Exercises
WorkoutDescription: We're entering a short high weight phase, you should warm up with a few of the core and isometric hip drive exercises before doing the squats and dead lift work. Squats - do 2 sets x 12 reps @ light to moderate weight. Goal is keeping the movement pattern familiar but starting to give way to increased intensity on the bike. Follow each squat set with a 60 sec recovery, and then 5x squat jumps or box jumps. Recover for 3 min between sets. Dead lift - 2 sets x 12 reps @ light weight Add in these isometric hip drive exercises: 10-15 reps single leg hamstring bridge; start with one set and build to 3 (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmfTpRpf6LQ) Single leg squat (8-10 reps each side), only go as deep as you can control motion / not have knee diving in; start with one set build to 3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_Ca2YRRdtE Single leg deadlift/hip hinge with kettle bell (2-3 sets x 8-12 reps) Split hip drive exercises with these core exercises: Stir the pot, 8-10x clockwise, 8-10x counter clockwise https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1m_ru6EpyRo Side plank with leg lift (5-10 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZZkgopVBPMg Plank with leg lift (20x each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNcpxsUOj1Q Hamstring stretch in door frame, 60-90 sec each side (post workout and again pre bed, 2-3x per day).
CoachComments: Let's work this back in now that we have a bit of space from the race season.
AthleteComments: *09/13/2019 Matti Rowe: Yeah I skipped the squat jumps - the DOMS is OMS from Sanitas.* *09/17/2019 Nate Wilson: Yeah good call. I would actually skip the squat jumps maybe another week, especially if doing some running. We want to stress those tendons a bit, but not just ram the door.*

Title: Hill Sprints (6x)
WorkoutDescription: 10-20 min easy jogging warm up Then on a moderately steep hill (5-8%) do some sprints... 6x12 sec maximum sprints, focus on picking up knees and a quick turnover rather than long bounding steps. Recover for 1.5-2 min between each sprint. Rest of the time easy jogging to complete 30-60 min of total running.
AthleteComments: *10/14/2019 Nate Wilson: How'd these feel? I put them in for a few reasons. Largely I think it's just good for an "athlete health" perspective - cross training and getting away from the bike. But physically, these hill sprints really work on hip drive, which really helps in the TT bike and just build power - but in a way that's not us out doing it on the bike.* *10/14/2019 Matti Rowe: They felt strange - I never sprint on foot. It was kind of interesting seeing how physically demanding it was. I was definitely feeling it on the 6th rep.*

On the squats - do them with the motion of a 3 sec slow drop, 1 sec pause at bottom, and then explode up hard. We'll use the DL and squat to build the higher weight work, and keep everything more in a light/maintenance position. I'd also suggest we add a split squat with your back leg elevated, this can help with the isometric hip drive as well. I'm going to update the workout a bit for the next few weeks and you take a look and let me know what you think.*

Title: Sprint Work (4x stomps, 2x stands)
WorkoutDescription: Sprint workout today. Warm up, including 1x10min 270-300w @ 105+ rpm, then some sprints: -2x15sec seated sprints in the little ring, only shifting when you're really running out of gear, keep upper body quiet. -4x20sec "stomps", done seated, in a big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, should only be hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so (adjust gear as necessary). -2x20sec standing starts, done in big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, again hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so. Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min).
AthleteComments: *11/12/2017 Matti Rowe: Shifter cable snapped before Iï¸ could get to the stands.* *11/13/2017 Nate Wilson: Bummer but also probably good that it didn't snap while you were full fuck out of the saddle in your biggest gear!*

Title: Baseline Aerobic Limit Ride
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy warm up to get legs going. Then, goal is aerobic stress. High average power without going over Z3/Tempo (320w) Pick a route where you can stay fairly constant on the pedals, and minimize soft pedaling and coasting. Target a lot of time @ High Z2/Low Z3 (230-280w) 10min easy cool down to flush the effort.
AthleteComments: *11/11/2017 Matti Rowe: Sorry man pinched for time today.  Looks like similar wattage and 8 beats higher.  I'll make us proud another day.* *11/13/2017 Nate Wilson: No sweat - probably just showing that you're a bit fresh this week which is not super surprising.*

Title: Staying Power
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min @ 3h limit pace (270-290w). So this is tough, but it should potentially just be biting by the end. If it feels easy - that is great - doesn't mean you need to add wattage. Just loading up the legs a bit - Sat/Sun are priority. Throw in 2-3 x 5 min blocks in "aero" position @ 105+ rpm
AthleteComments: *11/20/2017 Nate Wilson: Check, check - good to see HR looking fresh coming into the weekend.*

Title: Rhythm Change, Bookended by LT
WorkoutDescription: 30-45m Z1/Z2 warm up, ramp to upper Z2 for a bit before hitting the first effort. Efforts in this order with full recovery between: 1. 10 min Z4 (start low and aim for repeatability for now - still a bit early for gut busting max) 2. 15 min Z3 with a 15 sec acceleration every 3m 3. 10 min Z4 Easy cool down shake out home, save any extra energy for tomorrow!
AthleteComments: *11/20/2017 Nate Wilson: Good efforts! How'd they feel?* *11/20/2017 Matti Rowe: I could not have repeated the last 10m again because I was on tap out nutritionally.* *11/20/2017 Nate Wilson: OK - good feedback. Keep that in mind - a lot of time that threshold power, people have the repeatability moreso than they think if they're taking in a ton of carb.*

Title: Long End w/ Tempo Finish

Title: La Luz Dreaming
WorkoutDescription: The aim for this week is two-fold: 1. Getting general miles, volume, and aerobic load in. 2. Getting away from structure for a week, so that you're putting in work, but without the mental stress of going hard on demand. You can get in vol as you like and as life allows - enjoy it! Cross training is fine!

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.
CoachComments: I don't care what days this is on, but let's aim for 2x this week

Title: Hvile or Light Aerobic
WorkoutDescription: I'd say either light spin or light roller ski if you want to do something, probably better to shy away from the impact of running.

Title: Sprint Work (4x stomps, 4x stands)
WorkoutDescription: Sprint workout today. Warm up, including 1x10min 270-300w @ 105+ rpm, then some sprints: -2x15sec seated sprints in the little ring, only shifting when you're really running out of gear, keep upper body quiet. -4x20sec "stomps", done seated, in a big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, should only be hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so (adjust gear as necessary). -4x20sec standing starts, done in big gear, from a near stop (<10 mph), max acceleration, again hitting 100 rpm in the last 5 sec or so. Full recovery between sprints (minimum = 2min).

Title: Strength
WorkoutDescription: Foundations/yoga moves to get loose This week, start bumping the weights up, moving to 2 sets of 8 reps of heavier weights on the squats. Prior to each set of squats, do a set of 5 box jumps, then 2 min recovery, then squats.

Title: Rhythm Change, Bookended by LT
WorkoutDescription: 30-45m Z1/Z2 warm up, ramp to upper Z2 for a bit before hitting the first effort. Efforts in this order with full recovery between: 1. 15 min Z4 (start low and aim for repeatability for now - still a bit early for gut busting max) 2. 15 min Z3 with a 15 sec acceleration every 3m 3. 15 min Z4 Easy cool down shake out home, save any extra energy for tomorrow!
CoachComments: 2-3h, whatever you have time for - shorter is fine - focus on quality over vol today.
AthleteComments: *12/11/2017 Matti Rowe: Ran into Clemence on second interval so that got messed up* *12/11/2017 Nate Wilson: All good. Looks like you hit highest on the last rep, good work! And weight trending down, nice job Matti! Only additional thing Iâ€™d add is on the weekends, when you have more time itâ€™d be good to do these LT reps on more of a climb. Nothing crazy, but Iâ€™ve found with myself itâ€™s easy to get in a rut where you can make the power on the shallower grades but when it gets more 6-8 percent itâ€™s a different feeling - and thatâ€™s what weâ€™re training for. Â¯\_(ãƒ„)_/Â¯* *12/18/2017 Nate Wilson: Yeah, torque for sure is an element, sometimes you just don't have the gradient (or gear, whatever way you want to look at it) to do the cadence you're most comfortable making power at - so if you can do 380w for 20min @ 95 rpm, but all of a sudden at 85 rpm you can't handle the torque for that duration it changes. The other factor is a bit more anecdotal and I don't have a good grasp on the biomechanics, but if you think about it from a gravity perspective - force of gravity is always straight down, as gradient changes though, the "effective vector" changes and can shift a bit how you're applying force to the pedals against gravity - so I think the sensation can just be quite different. Title: Rhythm Change + VO2 wake up
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 2x15min climbs that are 10min holding 300-330w baseline with a 10 sec surge every 2min < 5min steady Z4 RPE 8-10 min recovery between Finish with 1x4min VO2 effort Cool down
AthleteComments: *01/10/2018 Matti Rowe: I'm sorta always riding the ragged diet edge right now, so I felt underfueled during the intervals.  In the future I'm going to hit a big bowl of oatmeal 3 hours before higher intensity workouts.* *01/15/2018 Nate Wilson: OK yeah - you nailed that. Running these workouts with good carb in your system is key. I would even say the way to think about it is actually look at dinner the night before as one of your more important meals. That way your body really hast time to store it as glycogen. It's less about the sensation of fullness and more about having the glyco stores topped. So what I usually do is if the next day is high intensity - have a good portion of carbs with dinner the night before. Then the next day eat normally knowing you have the glycogen topped up, and you don't need to stuff yourself and feel bloated.* *01/15/2018 Matti Rowe: OK roger that that makes a lot of sense. I think I had a salad the night before with avocado and chicken so I wasn't really filling up the glycogen stores.*

Title: Aerobic Load Sprints + LT Builder (3x8)
WorkoutDescription: 2.5-3h total as follows: 60min Z1/Z2 warm up 45min block holding upper Z2 baseline (280w ceiling), every 5min do a hard 8 sec sprint from a light gear (9x sprints total). Title: VO2 + Over/Under

Full recovery between all. Cool down

Title: 3x8 TT Speed
WorkoutDescription: Progressive warm up, capped with 5min tempo 95+ rpm. Flush legs. 3x8m @ RPE 8-9, make the recovery time however long it takes to ride back to the start point so that you do these all on the same stretch of road. Gauge these on RPE more than a given #, at least to start. First two reps, lock in on "hard, controlled", final rep try to get to a farther point down the road than the first 2 reps. Go as easy as you like home, don't think about power.
CoachComments: On the 3x8, think about position on the bike and riding slightly undulating power to maximize speed across the stretch of road you're on.
AthleteComments: *03/19/2018 Matti Rowe: Wind was nuts.  Also, on a new TT bike that's actually my size.*

Today you did 15min @ 370w after 2700 kJ - so not apples to apples, but considering the fatigue in the legs, I think that is a solid effort! Good to see this week build as it did.* *03/26/2018 Nate Wilson: I'd like to see you stick to Monday/Tuesday fairly easy as planned, you could add some 5min progressions on Tuesday from low tempo to low threshold, but you shouldn't do any more than that. Freshness is good now.*

Title: Climbing Endurance w/ surges - Fearsome Foursome
WorkoutDescription: 5-6h old school endurance - don't worry about specific structure or metrics, just get a big day in the mountains. Through the day include 20-25 x 6-8 sec surges. Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Title: Tired Legs Mix
WorkoutDescription: 15min easy easy warm up to get loose, during that time gradually work cadence to 100+ a few times. 5x20 sec on / 40 sec off (make the 20s increase each rep, first rep 350, then - 375, 400, 425, 450) - this is an opener. 10-15min Z3 RPE climb (alt 1.5 min seated / 30 sec standing) 4-6 x 80 sec "buffers" 20 sec out of the saddle @ 450+ watts < 60 sec @ 350w; 2-3 min recovery between. Cool down
AthleteComments: *04/01/2018 Matti Rowe: I did this immediately after pounding about 1500kjs of Easter Brunch and was nauseous but got something done.* *04/02/2018 Nate Wilson: Looks pretty solid all things considered, and if nothing else it's just good to get some of that mental stim of tired legs, waking up and still getting up for it.*

Title: 15/4 TT Workout (Lefthand)
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min progressive warm up building from easy to Z2 10min low Z3, 95+ rpm Then some TT efforts on lefthand. Start at lefthand/36 do 15min at TT pace where RPE is strong, but in control. Immediately flip it at start descending, ride in sticks where comfortable - power is easy, but keep leg speed 100+ rpm when pedaling. At bottom, turn around, ride 30 sec active recovery, then do 1x4min race pace - really open up the throttle on this one, stay in sticks for 3min then it's ok to get out and drive the last min if you feel you'll do more power that way. Easy spin home.
AthleteComments: *04/04/2018 Matti Rowe: Power is coming around in the new position.  Goddamn that bike feels good.* *04/09/2018 Nate Wilson: Love it man! If you can do those #s here, you can do them at Gila with a bit of race adrenaline and pressure. Looks like you started the 15 piece probably a bit hard - good to keep in mind for that first climb pacing at Gila. Were you able to stay in the sticks for most of the 4min?* *04/09/2018 Matti Rowe: I stayed in the sticks for the entire 4m effort. I let sensations dictate after 2min because I was doing more power than I normally do on a TT bike.  I kept waiting for the wheels to really fall off but they didn't. Go figure.  Â¯\_(ãƒ„)_/Â¯*

Title: 5x5 Varied
WorkoutDescription: Warm up, including 12min low Z3, 100+ rpm, then the meat of it: 5x5min on / 4min off with specificity - 1. 380-400w steady 2. 40 hard / 20 easy 3. 400-425w steady 4. 40 hard / 20 easy 5. 420+ steady Cool down
AthleteComments: *04/05/2018 Matti Rowe: The legs def had some yesterday in them but they came around.  The first effort felt the worst, strangely.* *04/09/2018 Nate Wilson: I think that's pretty common to have the first effort really suck then you come around - it's just like "strong, but tired" where it takes a little effort to ride through the initial crap but then you get to the core and have some get up and go. These #s are quite solid - that final 5min is less about a super flash 5min power, because you're pretty loaded up by the time you get to it and more getting there and still being able to hit some top end - so to do 448w is a good show! Quality two days here Matti!*

Title: Race (Cancelled) - Mixed VO2max Subsistute
WorkoutDescription: Ride there to warm up, including 3-4 x 60-90 sec lifts from 300w to 450w at 100+ rpm; goal here is doing enough to not be shocked off the line, but not really adding in a significant extra amount of work. For this race - the big takeaway I'd say is just another day striving for good positioning, and good nutrition. This race is so easy to get caught up in the chaos and get way behind on nutrition - aim for that 65-70 g of carbs per hour mark. Bonus - if feeling great - finish with 1x15min Z3 climb after the race; only do this if you've eaten well and can do it productively.
