Title: TT Strength Touch Up
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up 5min build from 260w to 360w 4x5min 300-330w, 60-70 rpm (as terrain allows, don't stress if you get above) / 4min recovery between @ 210-240w (so not full easy) 5min recovery after this block, then - 3x90 sec @ 360-400w / 2min recovery Cool down
AthleteComments: *05/07/2018 Matti Rowe: Strength set felt good, 90 sec felt brutal - def holding on the last 15 sec of each.* *05/07/2018 Nate Wilson: Nice, good to get back into it. Well you went too hard on the 90s. The last 30s of the ones you faded on were still 420w. With these - the idea is more about constant power - so just adding to the time in a given power bin that you spend time in when racing, not necessarily max stuff. I know you can do more than 360-400w for 90 sec; but the idea is just throwing some small chunks around the high end of race pace; so you stay familiar there without really crushing yourself to do so.*

Title: Buffer Progressions + 30/30
WorkoutDescription: Mixed efforts: 3x12min - first min ride ~400-440w, then settle into a progression of... 3.5min 300-330w 4min 330-360w 4min 360-390w Space as you like - ok to do on short recovery as long as you feel you can do well. 8x30 sec @ 450-500w (not max) / 30 sec recovery Cool down
AthleteComments: *05/07/2018 Matti Rowe: I wish I could tell you how I felt but all I remember is that it was pissing rain and I couldn't feel my feet.* *05/07/2018 Nate Wilson: Ouch! Proper Norwegian day.*

Title: Strength
WorkoutDescription: Foundations/yoga moves to get loose Go to lighter weights, squats should be 2 sets of 12 reps, on what feels like 20 rep max, on each rep go down slow, slight pause at the bottom, then accelerate up hard. Prior to each set of squats, do a set of 8 box jumps, then 2 min recovery, then squats. Towards the end of the workout, another set of plyo exercises: 2sets x 8 reps split squat jumps (8 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK7xI0wa04g Finish with stretching and foam rolling.
CoachComments: Let's aim for a couple sessions to touch up the body between now and Morgul
AthleteComments: *05/07/2018 Nate Wilson: Good to keep up with this!*

Title: Open Sensations
WorkoutDescription: No strict objectives - just a ride for the head and the heart - you can rip it today if you want.

Title: Sensations
WorkoutDescription: Nice and easy today, keep the cadence light and spend some time with the cadence over 100rpm to flush the legs a bit. 5x30 sec one leg drills
CoachComments: Easy flush if time
AthleteComments: *05/04/2018 Matti Rowe: Holy buckets!  I guess a + TSB helps, eh?  I seriously thought my PM was broken the first 4 minutes.* *05/07/2018 Nate Wilson: Nicely done! I'm glad you bought in and kept the lid on it last week - that recovery is what allows two weeks of going through the wringer to actually take hold.*

Title: Building Ride
WorkoutDescription: 25-30 min Z1/Z2 warm up, gear limited to the little ring, 105+ rpm where terrain allows, then efforts chunked through: 15 min Z3 @ 300-320w, can lift to Z4 last 3-4 min but otherwise just chill. Cut down efforts of: 8min 370-400w - 4min 390-430w - 2min 440-480w - 1min 500+ Full recovery between all (like actual full, at least 1:1 work/rest ratio). Finish with 4x80 sec buffers of 20 sec attack into 60 sec @ 350-380w; 2min recovery between. Comfy endurance the rest; 2.5-3h total.
AthleteComments: *05/05/2018 Matti Rowe: Fak messed up nutrition today and didn't bring enough - was running on fumes 2hrs in and didn't have the 80sec efforts in me - just tried to limp home in time.* *05/07/2018 Nate Wilson: All good. Great day the day prior - just all part of the human part of athletics.*

Title: Climbing Endurance
WorkoutDescription: 4-5 hours in the hills; no structured objectives - just a nice long aerobic builder in the saddle. Tempo on climbs is great as you feel. Don't need to walk in the door totally shattered from this one, but good to have a solid day. Great to go with a group and really just go on sensation.
CoachComments: Race day gut training - eat 70 g of carbs per hour.
AthleteComments: *05/07/2018 Matti Rowe: I ate heaps today and I felt freaking fantastic.  Correlation is NOT causation though Nate!* *05/07/2018 Nate Wilson: Right on! Glad we got a big eating day in - not just for ride quality but also just so your reminded what you need to do at Morgul.*

Title: 5x5 Varied
WorkoutDescription: Warm up, including 12min low Z3, 100+ rpm, then the meat of it: 5x5min on / 4min off with specificity - 1. 380-400w steady 2. 40 hard / 20 easy 3. 400-425w steady 4. 40 hard / 20 easy 5. 420+ steady Cool down
AthleteComments: *05/09/2018 Matti Rowe: I tried to get to the top of NCAR in 5 minutes on the last rep to challenge myself for fun and exploded 4min30 in.  Everything before that was on point so don't get too starchy with me.* *05/10/2018 Matti Rowe: Or was it?  Do you want me to go harder on the 40 sec efforts?  I just try to stay above 450.* *05/14/2018 Nate Wilson: I think execution on this was perfect. On the 40s you want to go hard, but usually doing this workout well means that you could go harder on the 40s - because if you really really whack them the 5min efforts suffer. So yeah it's kind of about the accumulation of the body of work, rather than really really ripping the 40s at max. So yeah they look good - solid workout!*

Title: Mixed Over/Under

AthleteComments: *05/22/2018 Nate Wilson: Looks like HR was getting up just fine, so I think we were shedding the fatigue alright. How'd you feel? This feel alright as a "bridge" workout, with the goal of staying opened up and ready to go hard on the weekend, but not really cooking yourself physically or mentally?* *05/22/2018 Matti Rowe: I felt great and this did the job for sure. Title: TT Opener Ride
WorkoutDescription: Ideally you recon the course today. Ride it once visualizing how you're going to pace it, pick out markers on the side of the road to let you know where you are during your ride. Pay attention to any sections of bad pavement and remember what part of the road to ride on. Once you've gotten loosened up with easy pedaling do some openers. 1x5min tempo @ 110+ rpm 1x5min threshold @ race cadence 1x30 sec hard effort
CoachComments: Tempo @ 280w Thresh @ 340-360w, not maxing 30 @ 450-500w

Title: TT Warm Up
WorkoutDescription: 12min ramp from Z1 to low Z3 (keep cadence high to elevate HR). 3min easy 3min progression from low Z4 to high Z4 2min easy 2-3 x 30 sec seated accelerations (just as much as you feel you need here, less is more) 1min easy between, roll to the line and go! PACING - strong start, but where you can really drop the ball on this is on the downhills - none of these downhills are so fast that you shouldn't be fairly on the pedals - aim for 350w on the downhills, and going over on the uphills - ride the downhills by sensation of speed as well as power, if you're getting over 35 mph, you can back off a bit and get quite small. Nice leisurely cool down to flush legs for tomorrow.
AthleteComments: *05/19/2018 Matti Rowe: Up is down, down is up kinda day. Power was good/great but I was slow AF.  I guess I push air like a bus again suddenly? Just pissed.* *05/19/2018 Matti Rowe: BBS has me at .315 CdA here.  .265 at Gila TT. Â¯\_(ãƒ„)_/Â¯* *05/22/2018 Nate Wilson: I agree power was really solid. You had weather pulled correctly and same equipment selections in BBS?* *05/22/2018 Matti Rowe: Yep. See attached pic.  I need to remember to keep my head by my hands.*

Title: RR
WorkoutDescription: Bottle at least 1x per lap. Food nearly 2x per lap, eating every 30-35 min - aim for 70 g of carbs per hour.
AthleteComments: *05/20/2018 Matti Rowe: I got in the early break!  We stayed away for 3 laps then another group of 303 dudes (I feel like 1/2 the field was 303) bridged and attacked.  That was my peak 1min right there trying to stay with it.  I couldn't. I did finish though, which I've never been close to fit enough to do. I also beat a lot of guys that by default think they're better than me.  So fuck those guys. Thanks for helping me get where I'm at.  I've never been faster than I am now!* *05/22/2018 Nate Wilson: Awesome man I'm glad you feel so good about this. This is a race where I think performance really is the best reflection of progress. This is one of those races where peak power #s are never really PRs because it's just hard all day, and so usually when folks have a bad day they look at the #s and feel even worse about it. So without being too patronizing I think realizing it's the first time you've finished and you were actually in the front end of the race for a bit is awesome progress. This race is also great prep for Salida. I feel like that climb at Salida is honestly a bit shorter and punchier and you can get over it. But yeah it will come down to a lot of reps. Thanks for thanking me but I think you owe it to yourself - you're the one busting your tail. You've done awesome work to slim down this year and that's been a really noticeable performance bump. It'll help even more as the summer keeps heating up.*

WorkoutDescription: Foundations/yoga moves to get loose Go to lighter weights, squats should be 2 sets of 12 reps, on what feels like 20 rep max, on each rep go down slow, slight pause at the bottom, then accelerate up hard. Towards the end of the workout, another set of plyo exercises: 2sets x 8 reps split squat jumps (8 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK7xI0wa04g Finish with stretching and foam rolling.

Title: Aerobic Load Sprints
WorkoutDescription: 5-10 min easy warm up, with 2-3 min ramp into tempo (< 350w) at the end. 50 min holding 250-270w baseline, do an 8 sec sprint from a light gear every 5min (10x total) Easy cool down
AthleteComments: *06/11/2018 Nate Wilson: Good yeoman session - great consistency on the sprints, all over 1100w except for one in the middle.*

Title: 3x8 TT Speed
WorkoutDescription: Progressive warm up, capped with 5min tempo 95+ rpm. Flush legs. 3x8m @ RPE 8-9, make the recovery time however long it takes to ride back to the start point so that you do these all on the same stretch of road. Gauge these on RPE more than a given #, at least to start. First two reps, lock in on "hard, controlled", final rep try to get to a farther point down the road than the first 2 reps. Go as easy as you like home, don't think about power.
CoachComments: On the 3x8, think about position on the bike and riding slightly undulating power to maximize speed across the stretch of road you're on.
AthleteComments: *06/06/2018 Matti Rowe: Didn't look at the power, just sensations. I was pleasantly surprised with the power since  the little strength sessions we've been doing really light up my glutes which seem to be more activated in the TT position.* *06/11/2018 Nate Wilson: Power looks good in these. I do think doing them on lefthand makes it a bit easier to do the power. On one hand maybe not as if you look at the segment you were doing it was just 2% avg, but yeah you do get some good uphill to push against. For this weeks workout, I'd be interested to have you do some more on flats and then actually maybe finish on the climb and try to push more wattage on the final piece - essentially as the interval duration drops the power goes up. Maybe a good route would be: Int 1 - start on Niwot from 75th to 36, turn R on 36 as it'll be under 15' Then the recovery, then start the 10' piece and turn onto lefthand, then descend down for the 5' recovery and do the final 5' piece. You get some gradient help through there, but you also get some little flats and downhills as well to deal with staying on the pedals with.*

Title: Strength
WorkoutDescription: Foundations/yoga moves to get loose Go to lighter weights, squats should be 2 sets of 12 reps, on what feels like 20 rep max, on each rep go down slow, slight pause at the bottom, then accelerate up hard. Prior to each set of squats, do a set of 8 box jumps, then 2 min recovery, then squats. Towards the end of the workout, another set of plyo exercises: 2sets x 8 reps split squat jumps (8 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK7xI0wa04g Finish with stretching and foam rolling.

Title: Tempo/LT 2x20
WorkoutDescription: 2x20min alternating 4min 300-330w / 1min 370-400w; space as you like, but at least 8min recovery between preferably. Otherwise just riding.
CoachComments: This is more of a maintenance workout than a real crusher - bear with it
AthleteComments: *06/07/2018 Matti Rowe: It felt really easy to knock these out. Hungry AF right after the last rep tho.* *06/11/2018 Nate Wilson: Check, check - glad to hear these felt easy!*

AthleteComments: *06/11/2018 Nate Wilson: Great power there - looks like you came off the drive well!*

Title: Sandia Crest RR
WorkoutDescription: EATING EATING EATING!
AthleteComments: *06/11/2018 Nate Wilson: Interesting to hear how you felt on this one. It's an interesting race, nearly like a guanella or something but with some racing beforehand. HR sure was up - I'd chalk it up to heat largely in the beginning. Yeah nothing earth shattering on the #s, so interested to hear how you felt.* *06/11/2018 Matti Rowe: I felt good! I was pretty much racing for 3rd since Fortu and Amundsund are about .5w/kg better than me so I spent as little energy as I could without being inattentive until the foot of the climb and then it just broke up.  Fortunato just rode away, and I held on in the second group of Moro and Amundsund as long as I could but let them go because I knew it was an hour long effort and I didn't want to explode and drop 10 places.  Eating and drinking was spot on, but I admit I felt pretty destroyed in the last few switchbacks and was relieved when the line came into view.  Rolled in 4th place.*

Title: HVILE or Easy Spin
WorkoutDescription: Your call - active recovery or day off based on what you have time for.

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Title: End Sensations w/ Spin Ups
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min endurance ride guided by sensation more than power. It shouldn't be much over 260w and doesn't need to be a 300w staying power ride - even if feeling great. On the flip side, stay a bit light if fatigued and let yourself unload. Every 15min do 30 sec @ 120+ rpm to get things loose.

Title: TT Cut down (15/10/5)
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up with a few 30 sec lifts to Z3/Z4 power @ 105+ rpm to get loose, then efforts: 15min @ 330-360w (5min recovery) 10min @ 330-360w (5min recovery) 5min @ 330-360w (cool down) This is about an accumulation of time at a power that is solid but that you can do and how it adds up (30min of work total) - so better to start low on the power band and ramp through it if you feel good, than to blow yourself trying 360w in the first piece and then not recover for the 10min piece.
AthleteComments: *06/15/2018 Matti Rowe: Missed this - bad time management.*

Title: Strength

Prior to each set of squats, do a set of 8 box jumps, then 2 min recovery, then squats. Towards the end of the workout, another set of plyo exercises: 2sets x 8 reps split squat jumps (8 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK7xI0wa04g Finish with stretching and foam rolling.

Title: 40/20's Ride
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 15-20min @ 300-330w to ding the legs a bit. 2-3 sets of 10x40 sec @ 440-480w / 20 sec easy (8min recovery between sets); Only do 3rd set if you have time and can do it at that wattage. Cool down
AthleteComments: *06/17/2018 Matti Rowe: I had great legs.  Looking back, I also felt like I might be getting sick, and that proved to be true.  It's funny, but over the years I've noticed that  sometimes right before you fall off the edge your body gives you one more good day before it breaks down.* *06/18/2018 Nate Wilson: I've seen the same thing repeatedly. A lot of time when someone gets sick it seems like they're riding really well. I've always wondered if it's chicken or egg, in the sense that are you riding well because you've done a good load and fitness is high, but getting there has also spread you thin so you get sick. Or is it more something like in getting sick, yeah you get some last pop of energy - I don't know anything about what sort of mechanism that would be - could be something with the immune system mobilizing.*

WorkoutDescription: Nice and easy today, keep the cadence light and spend some time with the cadence over 100rpm to flush the legs a bit. 5x30 sec one leg drills
CoachComments: Easy flush if time

Title: Cycling
AthleteComments: *06/15/2018 Matti Rowe: I tried the TT cut workout and ate shit. I woke up with congestion and ennui. I rode anyway, tried to push, nothing.  Just rolled Z2, had a nice, annoying stop for a railroad puncture, and tried not to hate myself on the way back.* *06/18/2018 Nate Wilson: Ah glad you didn't push through this too much. Everyone's going to have bad days in training. When they happen in training, they don't matter that much at the end of the day.*

Title: Climbing Endurance w/ 4' pop
WorkoutDescription: 4-5 hours in the hills; no structured objectives - just a nice long aerobic builder in the saddle. Tempo on climbs is great as you feel. Sometime in the first 2h, after you've done a bit of tempo to warm up, pick a segment of climb that is +/- 4' (ideally < 7000 feet) and go hard, like a bit of a taste of the Baker City uphill TT. Don't need to walk in the door totally shattered from this one, but good to have a solid day. Great to go with a group and really just go on sensation.
CoachComments: Race day gut training - eat 70 g of carbs per hour. ---- If tight on time, opt for a 2-3h ride with increased workload as follows: 3-4 x 10min progressive efforts of 6min Z3 (300-330w) < 2.5 min Z4 (370-400w) < 1.5 min Z5 (420-460w)
AthleteComments: *06/16/2018 Matti Rowe: AHHHHHH my fucking Garmin ate this ride.  I did this: https://www.strava.com/routes/13839092* *06/17/2018 Matti Rowe: My sinuses are acting up and they ran like crazy today but I also had good legs.  4min effort went well and the power stayed on all day (I ate and drank well).  I might be 1 wheels short of a dualie though and wake up with a sore throat and worse nose.* *06/18/2018 Nate Wilson: Bummer we lost the power on the 4min effort - but if you felt good I'm stoked on it! But yeah sounds like we may need to back off a bit this week.*

Title: ALT - 2h w/ Mixed Tempo
WorkoutDescription: 20-30 min easy warm up 2x15min alternating as follows: 5min steady Z3 (300-330w) 5min of 20s 450w / 40s 280w 5min steady Z3 (300-330w) If you feel super whacked today - just go comfortable endurance.
AthleteComments: *06/17/2018 Matti Rowe: I was surprised to wake up and find that my sinuses weren't worse after yesterdays's monster ride. I was whacked tho, and just cruised.  I got home and randomly fell asleep (I never nap) so I'm glad I didn't dig a deeper whole and risk giving my sinuses a foothold.* *06/18/2018 Nate Wilson: Could just be a bit of a heat induced fatigue - good not to push today. Let's see how you're doing come Tuesday. If you feel A+ Tuesday I'm fine keeping the rest of the week the same. But if you don't feel that good Tuesday, I'd prefer you not to do the big LT cut down on the TT rig.*

Title: 5x5 Varied
WorkoutDescription: Warm up, including 12min low Z3, 100+ rpm, then the meat of it: 5x5min on / 4min off with specificity - 1. 380-400w steady 2. 40 hard / 20 easy 3. 400-425w steady 4. 40 hard / 20 easy 5. 420+ steady Cool down
AthleteComments: *06/21/2018 Matti Rowe: Another day of inferior genetics on display.  If we set that aside, fueling may have played a role - I thought I ate enough last night but I was pretty light this morning (for an obese Norwegian).* *06/25/2018 Nate Wilson: Without knowing exactly what your 24h was like - I wouldn't be surprised if you were low on fuel. This is one of the most carb intensive workouts you can do - other than doing this workout after just more kJs. But yeah those afters are all carb. They actually don't look bad, pushing 428w on that final rep until you pulled the plug is solid - but yeah sounds like you just didn't have control of the effort. Title: General Climbing Endurance
WorkoutDescription: General endurance today, can throw in some tempo/threshold as you feel, but not a crusher day. Would prefer to see tomorrow be the harder of the days.
CoachComments: Let's use this weekend to really have race nutrition dialed for next week - aim for ~65-70 g of carbs per hour both days.
AthleteComments: *06/25/2018 Nate Wilson: Interested to hear how you felt - to me 53min @ 355w @ 2300 m avg elevation is a great one for you! Looks like it's your second best 60 min power ever, and the effort was not really even 60 min long. Best since 2013! It's a pretty nice real world confirmation of FTP @ 360w. But really if we were to say "1% increase in power per 1000 ft elevation)" this would maybe be like a 362w at Boulder "constant" elevation - but that's pretty close. Maybe this wasn't fully flat out, so maybe we could have FTP at 370w, but I'm not sure it really changes anything on our day to day implementation. Maybe CTL drops a bit, but yeah I'm happy with FTP 360w for now.* *06/25/2018 Matti Rowe: I felt fantastic!  I could just push and push - I think I could have given a bit more but the day wasn't done in Ward.  Shortly thereafter I followed a move which was 500+ watts for a minute up pretty high so I def wasn't totally gased. I'm more than fine leaving my FTP at 360 - I think that's about right. Maybe tapered on a really good day I'm 10 watts higher for an hour, but let's be honest that's not my 'level' right now.* *06/25/2018 Nate Wilson: OK sweet!*

Title: Big Climbing Day
WorkoutDescription: No structured objectives, just a big day in the saddle. Plenty of tempo on the climbs - eat up!
AthleteComments: *06/25/2018 Nate Wilson: Looks like you shaved some time off from when you went flat out up sugarloaf last month - and a much stronger finish. Today last 14min = 387w, last time 337w. Nice! How hard did this day feel overall? How'd you do with fueling?* *06/25/2018 Matti Rowe: It felt fine honestly.  The biggest takeaway from this weekend is if you want to go hard often you have to carb up before, during, and after to support the efforts.  If you carb up you can go, if you don't eat enough then that extra gear just isn't there.* *06/25/2018 Matti Rowe: BTW epic conditions on Berthoud.  I was in the front group of 5 going over it and we immediately descended.  10m later a blizzard came through.* *06/25/2018 Nate Wilson: Yes, I agree 100% with what you said about the carbs. Takes sometime to develop the intrinsic sense of what that equates to in terms of implementation, but it's key! There's a big jump from 320w to 370w, and that jump is very carb intensive. Ha I actually was driving back to Denver from Grand Lake and saw y'all coming up from Empire - had a feeling you might meet some frosty conditions. Great job climbing up with the front guys! Let's get you some easy days and then into Baker City - you're in good knick!*

Title: Short PoP

WorkoutDescription: 1-2h easy ride with some efforts to open up: 5min low Z3 (by RPE), 95+ rpm 2min at 5min max RPE 10-15 sec sprint Full recovery between all efforts.

Title: Baker City RR
WorkoutDescription: Pay attention to heat and make sure you're drinking from the onset. Seems like this could be a great one for a break to get up the road and take advantage of a negative racing situation. Afterwards get 1L of fluid with electrolyte mix down in the 45 min post finish - all about recovery for that PM TT.
AthleteComments: *06/30/2018 Matti Rowe: Big field, couldn't get up, got detached from the lead group on the 1.5mile dirt section. Almost got back on the climb, but didn't quite have the legs. Finished 1:49 down on winner, ~90sec on field.* *07/02/2018 Nate Wilson: Do you feel like you were struggling with the pace from the get go more or the positioning etc?* *07/02/2018 Klokka Skaddla: Just positioning. I had great legs!*

Title: TT w/ Warm Up
WorkoutDescription: Warm up - 15-20 min easy spin including recon of the course (if possible), then start your formal warm up - get your headphones on and just focus: 10min progression from easy finishing up ~300w, keeping cad mostly 95+ rpm 2min easy 3min build of 330 < 360 < 390 2min easy 90sec build in 30sec steps of 400 < 425 < 450 2min easy 10-15 sec seated acceleration Flush legs, roll to the line. 15-20 min cool down to really get HR down and let legs unload - definitely sipping electrolyte fluid.
CoachComments: Look at the course and if there's any real steep pitches plan on going a bit harder on steep pitches but staying on the gas long enough to really get momentum up on the flat before backing off. If fairly constant - target ~440w to start and see if you can gradually raise it from there. --- Looks like it starts somewhat gradual then just ratchets up as it goes, so definitely a negative split course.
AthleteComments: *06/30/2018 Matti Rowe: 475 beats expectations but still isn't good enough and I started with the 3rd place finisher who made me look ridiculous. Maybe could have snagged a couple seconds at the end if I knew where it actually finished, but couldn't preview beforehand.* *07/02/2018 Nate Wilson: Yeah I'm happy with that power as well! But yeah looks like it was a deep field, and that is just an explosive uphill w/kg effort that is maybe a bit out of your wheelhouse.*

Title: TT Warm Up
WorkoutDescription: 12min ramp from Z1 to low Z3 (keep cadence high to elevate HR). 3min easy 3min progression from low Z4 to high Z4 2min easy 2-3 x 30 sec seated accelerations (just as much as you feel you need here, less is more) 1min easy between, roll to the line and go! PACING - focus on position and speed more than power. Looks slight downhill out, so really yeah focusing on staying small, and then on the way back lift it up and try to mash a bit. Great avg would be 380w, but should be below 380w at the turnaround. Nice leisurely cool down to flush legs for the evening.
AthleteComments: *06/30/2018 Matti Rowe: So I focused on being small, and I think my CdA did improve from the S/M TT.  Best Bike Split thought it was .276, down from .29 which is still atrocious.  Power and time was meh. Out of answers in this discipline.* *07/01/2018 Klokka Skaddla: Can we fix that? Any ðŸ’¡? Lemolabs?* *07/02/2018 Nate Wilson: Yeah power was ok, not great for that elevation. Do you have any photos of you from Gila TT, Morg TT, and this one? I'd be interested just to start with a visual comparison, and then we can get into some of the other stuff. That article GC just put out about his push with TTing was good and gives some good food for thought with squeezing out gains in TTs.*

Title: PM Crit
WorkoutDescription: Stay out the sun for the time between TT and crit as much as possible. Get fed, stay off the legs and then maybe a nice afternoon coffee to get the energy flowing! Good luck!

Title: Baker City RR
WorkoutDescription: Big final day - eating and drinking all day.
AthleteComments: *07/01/2018 Matti Rowe: After the feed zone attacks flew on the downhills right before the final climb. I was on it but then a guy in front of me flatted, it killed my speed and the last 20 guys in the peloton blew by me.  I couldn't catch back on. For a final fuck you, the guy who flatted came blowing by me while hanging onto a car. Instead of burying myself so I could start the climb 3 minutes behind the lead group and fight for 30th place I just rode back. - Takeaways?: 1. It's cool I've lost some weight but I'm still too fat. 2. I don't know how to move in a pack well.  Good legs and good weight are great, but if you're in the back it doesn't matter because all your matches are going to be spent just getting back on terms with the front group when moves go. Any tips? Do more crits? 3. TT is back to disappointing.  Gila TT went well because it's less about CdA.  My CdA will never be elite but c'mon, there MUST be some way I can get it down in the .24-.25 range.  Any recommendations?* *07/02/2018 Nate Wilson: I don't know if I'd say you're too fat. There may be more weight to lose, but there's also a breaking point where you may be light for you, but that's also still just not killer w/kg light. And it may not be that you're too fat but it's just your a big guy and that's that. I think doing more crits is a good idea. Sounds like you lost a lot of energy in the two main RRs because of pack skills. Like this today with getting behind the guy with the flat is something I don't think of as something that should happen - you just have to force your way around, so some of it is aggression - using your size as an advantage. Let's look at some photos of the position, and maybe pull some of the slick tricks GC used and see if we can get you a bit slipperier.*

Title: Light TT Transition Work
WorkoutDescription: Easy ride on TT bike (not pegged 250w base), with some cadence transitions: 3x5min of 4min 280-320w 60-70 rpm < 1min 340-370w, 90-100 rpm Full recovery between.
AthleteComments: *07/09/2018 Nate Wilson: Baseline @ 296w, you did 2.3k in 3:50. Narrow @ 298w, you did 2.3k in 3:38. Baseline @ 346w, you did 2.32k in 3:38 Narrow @ 349w, you did 2.32k in 3:29 So both wattages the position change from baseline to narrow (what we settled on) saved ~10 sec over 2.3 km. You can see the speed differential was not massive between 300w and 350w (~3-4 kph), we'd expect that as speed differential goes up for the wattage gap (i.e. on a flatter terrain, i.e. 45+ kph) we'd see a bigger time differential (not necessarily on distance, but as a % of time) - so for a 3.5min chunk @ 40 kph maybe we're seeing ~10s, but at 50 kph it might be as much as 12-15s per 3.5 min. So yeah, I think that's pretty good savings. There's enough grey area that we can't say with full confidence ok it'll save X per 40km or something - I'm sure we'll see some variability. But I think we can say that this position is faster, within the range of significance, beyond the error of devices and human measurement. I used the 2.3k segment because it removes your start/stop that you did yourself, so hopefully removes some of that error. From today the closest thing we can say is that at a 40 kph avg TT, in a 20min TT this could be as much as 40-50 sec. It'll be interesting to see if that holds true!*

Title: Sunshine
WorkoutDescription: Warm up with easy riding over to the area, then do a 5min tempo, recovery, 3min threshold, recovery, 20-30 sec burst. Race, and then easy spin home. If feeling really sparky, could turn this into a volume day by riding home via P2P, but if not feeling great - better to just get home and recover.

Maybe legs would've been nothing special regardless, but I'm sure spending a couple hours getting boiled by the sun Saturday didn't help. I think it's all worth it in the long run. Title: TT: LT Cutdown (8/6/4/2)

Title: Loaded Tempo + Threshold Climb
WorkoutDescription: 3-4h depending on what you have time for, with efforts: -10min low Z3 on flats (270-300w), 95+ rpm -20min climb - first 5min alt 30 sec 420-480w / 30 sec 270-300w, into 15min @ 320-350w -20min climb - steady Z4 350-390w - not a maximum effort, but should be hard. At least 15min between efforts - when on open road can clip along pretty well @ 220-250w, but not much above that, let yourself go true easy for at least 10min after each effort then get back to Z2. 60-70 g of carbs per hour today, not just for today's quality, but also for recovery into tomorrow.

I slammed a Skratch Labs emergency pack right after. Not my best day out, but I'm proud I didn't bag it 90 minutes in after the crash and the flat. Hopefully I won't feel garbage tomorrow.* *07/23/2018 Nate Wilson: Ouch, that is a tough one! I'd say all things considered it's great that you powered through and got the work in. We'll throw some LT work in on Friday and you can get some redemption!*

Title: Col de Nelson TT (on road bike)
WorkoutDescription: Race day TT warm up: 15-20min easy spinning, progressing to low Z3 by the end; 2-3min flush after. 3min build increasing each min (330 < 360 < 390) 2min easy 90sec build increasing every 30" (390 < 420 < 450) 2min easy Wind up at the intersection of 63rd/Nelson. Do a TT effort that goes from 63/Nelson to 36/Nelson. Take it out fairly hard knowing the slowest section is at the start - but pace it such that you're getting the speed up on the flats and downhills and still driving it all the way to the finish. Easy cool down to finish the day.
CoachComments: A bit of specific prep for GMSR prologue - focus not just on wattage, but on getting small on the road bike when speed goes over 30 km/h

Focused more on power than getting small, but I was always in the bars, except for the small punch climbs.* *08/06/2018 Nate Wilson: You'll see the GMSR TT when you get there and once you see it iti'll be pretty evident what sections you should focus on power v aero. That's solid power and probably makes ~425-430w a good goal power for GMSR. But GMSR is one you can positive split pretty well actually to go fastest time, so you'll start out more aggressive being careful not to put yourself so far in the whole that you can't keep speed up once it flattens out.*

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Z1/Z2 warm up, concluding with a 10min progressive tempo building from 280w to 360w (last 2min @ 360w). 3 sets of: 20 sec hard (40 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 40 sec hard (20 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 20 sec hard (3min recovery between sets) Read "hard" for these as, hard but in control - essentially what feels good for that effort. Should be pushing the top end but never really telling yourself "hold on", "dig deep", "more power".
CoachComments: Goal is to do a bit of top end touch up, but also a workout that doesn't leave you crippled for the two days to come.
AthleteComments: *08/20/2018 Matti Rowe: Felt good - surpassed some 90 day wattage in the 20-40 sec range without really going for it.* *08/20/2018 Nate Wilson: Awesome, that's great the top end is alive and well. Hitting those higher register wattages will also keep the force familiar for going down to sea level.*

Title: Baller Climbing Workout (NCAR + Flag 3 ways)
WorkoutDescription: 45-60min Z1/Z2 warm up, then this gold standard Boulder climbing workout: -NCAR from broadway @ tempo (300-330w), once you hit Vassar (where road changes and grade kicks up), alternate 1min 300-330w / 30 sec out of the saddle @ 420-460w -Super Flag - to amphitheater @ 320-340w, top section increase as you feel by sensation. -Descend down backside -+/- 5min climb up to Gross accelerate hard the first steep pitch (~40 sec), then ride @ 300-330w the rest of the way (finish is when the road turns to dirt) -Turn around and descend -Z4 effort up backside Flag Finish out the day with easy spinning.
CoachComments: This is one nasty, nasty workout. Keep the tempo stuff controlled and on the low end of the ranges so that you can push on the higher end stuff. You'll need to stop after NCAR at a gas station or at Chataqua and get water.
AthleteComments: *08/19/2018 Matti Rowe: I felt good today and took a risk in overshooting some targets, Super Flag in particular, but I had the legs to back it up today.  I wasn't destroyed after the last interval (though I was starting to feel it a bit) - go figure. Saddle is up ~2cm. The one thing I really noticed is that I can produce more power in the saddle on climbs. It's almost like I'm getting a split second extra of recovery every pedal stroke, but am putting down the same power, so net I feel less buried.  I kinda thought it was all in my head, bc my SF time was 27:11, which is good (for me) but off my best, but interestingly the second half from the Amphitheater to the top was my 2nd best all time, only off 11 seconds from my PR, and I was carrying a flat kit and bottles which I never do if I'm going for a PR.  Huh!* *08/20/2018 Nate Wilson: That's a big differential in saddle - but sounds like it's super positive. Great to be that close to PR on the top part of Flag! Pretty encouraging you did 375w on flag and still were able to produce solidly on back side - great repeatability. 375w will probably translate to ~400w at sea level, so good to have the repeatability and pretty decent power to weight.*

Title: Kjekkfedre Tur
AthleteComments: *08/19/2018 Matti Rowe: Hike with Nick and the spawn discussing plans for next year.  Admittedly not an ideal preface to my attempt to be a Baller.*

Title: Long Climbing End w/ Surges
WorkoutDescription: 4.5-5.5h, with +/- 3000 meters of climbing. Ride most climbs @ 300-330w if feeling strong. Visual is just an old school, big day in the saddle, lot's of climbing - but also not digging super deep and doing much LT. If feeling well recovered and chomping, throw in a 20-25min LT climb after the 3h point, but rest of the time pretty controlled. Really aim to fuel well today @ 70-75 g of carbs per hour. 10-15x 10-12 sec seated surges spaced through the day.
CoachComments: https://dynamic-assets.mapmyfitness.com/routes/view/1633965973?host_canon=mapmyride.com 3rd RR is 100 miles w/10k of climbing and finishes on a SuperFlag like finish.
AthleteComments: *08/20/2018 Matti Rowe: Great legs. Stayed away from the LT bc I didn't want to go to the well and be in the box for 3 days. I struggled on the nutrition side today - I didn't start until almost noon, so by the time I started I had about 1300kcal in the fire which took me an hour to work through on the ride, so I didn't start eating until 90m in.  I also took a leftover hashbrown on the ride, which was a mistake, because it tanked my stomach, preventing me from really taking down more than 2 gels and a mojo until the last hour when I ate a snickers.  This is all to say I did not hit the 70g/hr mark, but intensity was in check so I never felt bad either. Just thought you should know. Also, lots of drop outs from the Stages today - looking into it.* *08/20/2018 Nate Wilson: Nice man what a great cap to the week! Yeah you can get away with that nutrition if you're not producing top end, but good to be aware of it. Race day you should be able to have a clearer idea of your schedule and control that a bit more. What head unit are you running? Seems like that's one of the biggest sources I've seen of Stages power drop.* *08/20/2018 Matti Rowe: I'm using the 520 - It's on a front Garmin mount so it's maybe 6" farther out than it was in the past. I like it out front - I can super tuck easier.*

Title: Front half recovery, back half stay open and sharp
Active Recovery
WorkoutDescription: 1h easy spin, HR < 120 bpm

Title: Strength (note slight changes)
WorkoutDescription: Foundations/yoga moves to get loose Go to lighter weights, squats should be 2 sets of 12 reps, on what feels like 20 rep max, on each rep go down slow, slight pause at the bottom, then accelerate up hard. After each set of squats, do a set of 8 box jumps, then 3-4 min recovery before starting next set. Follow with isolateral work... 3 sets x 8 reps (each leg) single leg squats, just body weight Towards the end of the workout, another set of plyo exercises: 2sets x 8 reps split squat jumps (8 reps each side) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK7xI0wa04g Finish with stretching and foam rolling.

Title: End Sensations w/ Spin Ups
WorkoutDescription: 60-90 min endurance ride guided by sensation more than power. It shouldn't be much over 260w and doesn't need to be a 300w staying power ride - even if feeling great. On the flip side, stay a bit light if fatigued and let yourself unload. Every 15min do 30 sec @ 120+ rpm to get things loose.

Title: 3x15 Mixed Climbs
WorkoutDescription: Warm up, then do 3x15min efforts on climbs: 1. 12min 300-330w < 3min 350-380w 2. 2.5min 320-350w / 30sec 420-450w 3. Steady 350-380w, can push more if feeling great but maintain control. 10-20min recovery between.
CoachComments: If for some reason the stars align and you can do a longer, 3-4h day today would be great. But I realize that's unrealistic - so just putting it here on the off chance.
AthleteComments: *08/24/2018 Matti Rowe: Good legs today, started nudging a bit on the last interval towards then end but everything felt firmly in my wheelhouse. 520 died, so I recorded rest of the ride on Fenix 3. Almost nabbed 4 hours.* *08/27/2018 Nate Wilson: Awesome, it all looks good. Good consistent roll you've got going here. Glad to see you absorbed last week well.*

Title: Foundation Work and Foam Rolling
WorkoutDescription: This routine doesn't take a lot of time, but is challenging and works. The focus is all on the posterior chain (read back, glutes, hamstrings). This will make you a better handler on the bike, better climber, and help cut out lower back pain. These are the muscle groups that cyclists often ignore, and pay the penalty for. Follow the link to the video: http://youtu.be/4BOTvaRaDjI Do some foam rolling and stretching after the foundation routine.

Title: Col de Nelson TT (on road bike)
WorkoutDescription: Race day TT warm up: 15-20min easy spinning, progressing to low Z3 by the end; 2-3min flush after. 3min build increasing each min (330 < 360 < 390) 2min easy 90sec build increasing every 30" (390 < 420 < 450) 2min easy Wind up at the intersection of 63rd/Nelson. Do a TT effort that goes from 63/Nelson to 36/Nelson. Take it out fairly hard knowing the slowest section is at the start - but pace it such that you're getting the speed up on the flats and downhills and still driving it all the way to the finish. Easy cool down to finish the day.
CoachComments: A bit of specific prep for GMSR prologue - focus not just on wattage, but on getting small on the road bike when speed goes over 30 km/h

WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, concluding with a 10min progressive tempo building from 280w to 360w (last 2min @ 360w). 3 sets of: 20 sec hard (40 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 40 sec hard (20 sec easy) 30 sec hard (30 sec easy) 20 sec hard (3min recovery between sets) Read "hard" for these as, hard but in control - essentially what feels good for that effort. Should be pushing the top end but never really telling yourself "hold on", "dig deep", "more power".
CoachComments: Goal is to do a bit of top end touch up, but also a workout that doesn't leave you crippled for the two days to come.
AthleteComments: *08/27/2018 Matti Rowe: Head was fixin' to do the TT sim so I went for it.  You were right - I was blocked!  That said, I had killer legs and still threw down decent power despite dying at the end.  Stoke is rippin for GMSR!*

Title: TT Opener Ride (1-1.5h based on what's available)
WorkoutDescription: Ideally you recon the course today. Ride it once visualizing how you're going to pace it, pick out markers on the side of the road to let you know where you are during your ride. Pay attention to any sections of bad pavement and remember what part of the road to ride on. Once you've gotten loosened up with easy pedaling do some openers. 1x5min tempo @ 60-70 rpm (focus on glute recruitment, and just getting straight on the bike) 1x5min threshold @ race cadence 1x30 sec hard effort
CoachComments: No power targets, gauge on RPE
AthleteComments: *08/31/2018 Matti Rowe: Flight got delayed so we got in late and then my bike was delivered without crank bolts or headset bolts.  Got into a shop 10m after it closed and they bailed me out.  So, no, didn't get to open it up.*

Title: TT
WorkoutDescription: 15-20min easy spinning, progressing to low Z3 by the end; 2-3min flush after. 3min build increasing each min (350 < 380 < 410) 2min easy 90sec build increasing every 30" (400 < 440 < 470) 2min easy Race - hard start but in control, and then transition to really focusing on speed in the second half - riding small, building momentum into steeper down sections and going steadier on shallower sections. Longish 20-30 min cool down to flush legs.

Title: Crit
WorkoutDescription: Try and spend some time on the course to warm up, but not so much that you overanalyze the corners. This is a really physical course that you can crush if you stay comfortable.

Title: Transition Strength Workout
WorkoutDescription: Read through the attached document and follow the instructions. The main goals here are to prevent injury by stretching the muscles that get shortened with cycling and also strengthening the overall body. Don't hesitate to ask if you've got any questions.
CoachComments: Let's keep doing some work over the next couple of months - but back off and make it a bit lighter. Let me know what you think, and if we want to mix in some more work we can. I'd like to see us in the big picture be back to lifting harder around December, and doing the meaty part of the workout as squats or hex bar deads followed by plyo - this is a great way to improve fast twitch recruitment, and get more out of your plyos.

Title: TT or Aerobic Load Sprints
WorkoutDescription: TT strength intro (4x6): Z1/Z2 warm up, gear limited to the little ring, 105+ rpm where terrain allows. Then efforts... 4x6min @ 300w / 3min recovery Do odd reps (1,3) @ 60-70 rpm Do even reps (2,4) @ 90-100 rpm Do as reps on Lefthand.
CoachComments: TT workout would be good if you're motivated, but ok to do aerobic load sprints instead.
AthleteComments: *09/13/2018 Matti Rowe: Back on the Canyon baby!* *09/17/2018 Nate Wilson: Nice man, I'm really glad you got these in. So much of being effective on the TT bike is just building up consistent reps in the position, pushing torque, pushing power, recruiting slow twitch fiber, and just getting comfortable being focused. As we start with these small pieces, even though they're not that hard - try to use each piece as a time to be fully focused on your effort and being smooth. As we bump out duration and ultimately at race time go to higher intensity - you want to bring the same mental attention that you'll have honed in these workouts.*

Title: Transition Strength Workout
WorkoutDescription: Read through the attached document and follow the instructions. The main goals here are to prevent injury by stretching the muscles that get shortened with cycling and also strengthening the overall body. Don't hesitate to ask if you've got any questions.
CoachComments: Let's keep doing some work over the next couple of months - but back off and make it a bit lighter. Let me know what you think, and if we want to mix in some more work we can. I'd like to see us in the big picture be back to lifting harder around December, and doing the meaty part of the workout as squats or hex bar deads followed by plyo - this is a great way to improve fast twitch recruitment, and get more out of your plyos.

Title: TT (3x12) + HC
WorkoutDescription: Z1/Z2 warm up, gear limited to the little ring, 105+ rpm where terrain allows. Then efforts: 3x12min 300-330w, 60-70 rpm / 5min recovery between. Do as reps on lefthand. Coming back in 36, do... 3x1min @ 320-350w, 110+ rpm / 1min recovery (prioritize cadence over power).
AthleteComments: *11/02/2018 Matti Rowe: Smh. I gotta hit up Zach again - my body has adapted to the road bike fit and now the TT fit feels fugged. Some adjustments helped, but it's just wrong. On the bright side, I got in 2 intervals in a TT position, which is way better than not having any time in a TT position.* *11/05/2018 Nate Wilson: Not to say that taking another look at the TT fit is a bad thing to do BUT I would also keep in mind that TT fit may feel bad just because you may have tightened up a bit in response to the new road fit. In my mind that doesn't necessarily mean change the TT fit to react - just give it a couple workouts and observe. I'd like to see if you feel any different this week on the TT workout. Sometimes you may just have days where you're not quite sitting on the TT bike right, but it doesn't necessarily mean changing the fit is the answer.* *11/05/2018 Matti Rowe: Copy that!*

Title: Winter Zones (FTP 360 --> 350)
WorkoutDescription: Matti, I'm just taking a touch off the FTP / zones as we move into winter. This is probably more reflective of where raw power will be post break. As you build back up we'll push up with time. For now you can keep these power zones in mind: FTP 350w ----------- 1/Recovery < 190w 2/Endurance 190-260 Low 3/Low Tempo 260-300 High 3/High Tempo 300-330 4/Threshold 330-370 5/VO2 Max 370-450 6/Supra Max 450+
